73575	Slayer	2011-07-06 18:58:01	<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n<articles loadtime="0 sec" rendertime="0.914 sec" totaltime="0.914 sec"><article><paragraph><template name="Other uses">\n</template><template name="Infobox musical artist">\n<param name="Name">Slayer</param>\n<param name="Img">Slayer, The Fields of Rock, 2007.jpg</param>\n<param name="Img_capt">Slayer performing at<space/><link><target>Fields of Rock</target></link><space/>in 2007.</param>\n<param name="Img_size">250</param>\n<param name="Landscape">yes</param>\n<param name="Genre"><link><target>Thrash metal</target></link>,<space/><link><target>speed metal</target></link></param>\n<param name="Background">group_or_band</param>\n<param name="Origin"><link><target>Huntington Park, California</target></link>,<space/><link><target>United States</target></link></param>\n<param name="Years_active">1981–present</param>\n<param name="Label"><link><target>Metal Blade Records</target><part>Metal Blade</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Def Jam Recordings</target><part>Def Jam</part></link>,<space/><link><target>American Recordings (US)</target><part>American</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Columbia Records</target><part>Columbia</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Sony Music Entertainment</target><part>Sony Music</part></link></param>\n<param name="Associated_acts"><link><target>Megadeth</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Testament (band)</target><part>Testament</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Overkill (band)</target><part>Overkill</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Malice</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Whiplash</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Grip Inc</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Forbidden</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Ice-T</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Body Count</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Truth About Seafood</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Cannibal Corpse</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Metallica</target></link></param>\n<param name="URL"><template name="URL">\n<param name="1">http://www.slayer.net/</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="Current_members"><link><target>Tom Araya</target></link><xhtml:br xmlns:xhtml=""/><link><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link><xhtml:br xmlns:xhtml=""/><link><target>Kerry King</target></link><xhtml:br xmlns:xhtml=""/><link><target>Dave Lombardo</target></link></param>\n<param name="Past_members"><link><target>Tony Scaglione</target></link><xhtml:br xmlns:xhtml=""/><link><target>Paul Bostaph</target></link><xhtml:br xmlns:xhtml=""/><link><target>Jon Dette</target></link></param>\n</template></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/0"><bold><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link></bold><space/>is an <link synthetic="true"><target>American Recordings (US)</target><part>American</part></link><space/><link><target>thrash metal</target></link><space/>band formed in<space/><link><target>Huntington Park, California</target></link>, in 1981 by guitarists<space/><link><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Kerry King</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/1"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> rose to fame with their 1986 release,<space/><italics><link><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Kerrang! Hall Of Fame"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerrang! Hall Of Fame</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">24 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://kerrang.typepad.com/kerrang_awards_2006_blog/2006/08/kerrang_hall_of.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerrang! Hall Of Fame</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">24 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://kerrang.typepad.com/kerrang_awards_2006_blog/2006/08/kerrang_hall_of.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and is credited as one of the "<link synthetic="true"><target>Big 4</target><part>Big</part></link> Four"<space/><link><target>thrash metal</target></link><space/>acts, along with<space/><link><target>Metallica</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Megadeth</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Anthrax (band)</target><part>Anthrax</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="last">Lee</param>\n<param name="first">Cosmo</param>\n<param name="title">Get Thrashed: The Story of Thrash Metal</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/movie_review/get-thrashed-the-story-of-thrash-metal.htm</param>\n<param name="work">Stylus</param>\n<param name="date">7 May 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 December 2008</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="last">Lee</param>\n<param name="first">Cosmo</param>\n<param name="title">Get Thrashed: The Story of Thrash Metal</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/movie_review/get-thrashed-the-story-of-thrash-metal.htm</param>\n<param name="work">Stylus</param>\n<param name="date">7 May 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 December 2008</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/2"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> musical traits involve fast<space/><link><target>tremolo picking</target></link>,<space/><link><target>double bass drumming</target></link>, and shouted vocals.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/3">The band's lyrics and album art, which cover topics such as<space/><link><target>serial killers</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Satanism</target></link>,<space/><link><target>religion</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>war</target><trail>fare</trail></link>, have generated album bans, delays, lawsuits and strong criticism from religious groups and the public.</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/4">Since their<space/><link><target>Show No Mercy</target><part>debut album</part></link><space/>in 1983, the band has released two<space/><link><target>live album</target><trail>s</trail></link>, one<space/><link><target>box set</target></link>, six<space/><link><target>music video</target><part>videos</part></link>, two<space/><link><target>extended play</target><trail>s</trail></link>, and eleven<space/><link><target>studio album</target><trail>s</trail></link>, four of which have received gold<space/><link><target>RIAA certification</target><part>certification</part></link><space/>in the <link synthetic="true"><target>United States</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/5">The band has received five<space/><link><target>Grammy Award</target><part>Grammy</part></link><space/>nominations, winning two of them; one in 2007 for the song "<link><target>Eyes of the Insane</target></link>", and one in 2008 for the song "Final Six".</sentence> <sentence id="73575/6"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> has played music festivals worldwide, including<space/><link><target>The Unholy Alliance Tour</target><part>Unholy Alliance</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Download festival</target><part>Download</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Ozzfest</target></link>.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="2">History</heading><heading level="3">Early days (1981)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/7"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> was founded in 1981, when guitarist<space/><link><target>Kerry King</target></link><space/>met<space/><link><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link><space/>while auditioning for a band.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Davis, Brian</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3153</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Davis, Brian</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3153</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/8">They recruited bassist and vocalist<space/><link><target>Tom Araya</target></link>, who had played with <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> before in the band Quits (previously known as Tradewinds).</sentence> <sentence id="73575/9">Drummer<space/><link><target>Dave Lombardo</target></link><space/>was recruited when he met <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> while delivering a<space/><link><target>pizza</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Drummerworld - Dave Lombardo"/><space/><sentence id="73575/10">The band played<space/><link><target>cover version</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Iron Maiden</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Judas Priest</target></link><space/>songs at clubs and parties in<space/><link><target>Southern California</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/11">Early shows relied on a<space/><link><target>Satanism</target><part>Satanic</part></link><space/>image, which featured<space/><link><target>pentagram</target><trail>s</trail></link>, make-up, spikes, and inverted crosses.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Allmusic Biography of Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Allmusic Biography of Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusicguide.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">artist</param>\n<param name="id">p5453/biography</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Allmusic Biography of Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusicguide.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">artist</param>\n<param name="id">p5453/biography</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/12">Rumors that the band was originally known as <link synthetic="true"><target>Dragonslayer</target></link>, after the 1981 movie of the same<space/><link><target>Dragonslayer</target><part>name</part></link>, were denied by <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link>, as he stated, "We never were; it's a myth to this day.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="Kerry King about the Dragonslayer myth, Christ Illusion, previous albums and experimenting"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerry King about the Dragonslayer myth, Christ Illusion, previous albums and experimenting</param>\n<param name="publisher">www.faceculture.nl</param>\n<param name="date">20 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.faceculture.nl/slayer/index.htm#</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20070104230520/http://www.faceculture.nl/slayer/index.htm#</param>\n<param name="archivedate">4 January 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">5 April 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerry King about the Dragonslayer myth, Christ Illusion, previous albums and experimenting</param>\n<param name="publisher">www.faceculture.nl</param>\n<param name="date">20 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.faceculture.nl/slayer/index.htm#</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20070104230520/http://www.faceculture.nl/slayer/index.htm#</param>\n<param name="archivedate">4 January 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">5 April 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/13">The band was invited to open for<space/><link><target>Bitch (band)</target><part>Bitch</part></link><space/>at the Woodstock Club in<space/><link><target>Los Angeles</target></link>, performing eight songs — six being covers.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/14">While playing <link synthetic="true"><target>Iron Maiden</target><part>Iron Maiden's</part></link> "<link><target>Phantom of the Opera (song)</target><part>Phantom of the Opera</part></link>" the band was spotted by<space/><link><target>Brian Slagel</target></link>, a former<space/><link><target>music journalist</target></link><space/>who had, at the time, recently founded the label<space/><link><target>Metal Blade Records</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/15">Impressed with <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> performance, <link synthetic="true"><target>Brian Slagel</target><part>Slagel</part></link> met with the band backstage and asked them to record an original song, "Aggressive Perfector" (<template name="Audio">\n<param name="1">Aggressive Perfector clip.ogg</param>\n<param name="2">sample</param>\n</template>), for his upcoming<space/><italics><link><target>Metal Massacre#Metal Massacre III – 1983</target><part>Metal Massacre III</part></link></italics><space/>compilation.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/16">The band agreed and the song created underground "buzz", which led to <link synthetic="true"><target>Brian Slagel</target><part>Slagel</part></link> offering the band a<space/><link><target>recording contract</target></link><space/>with <link synthetic="true"><target>Metal Blade Records</target><part>Metal Blade</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="INTERVIEW WITH BRIAN SLAGEL"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with Brian Slagel</param>\n<param name="author">German, Eric</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalupdate.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalupdate.com/interviewmetalblade.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">4 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with Brian Slagel</param>\n<param name="author">German, Eric</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalupdate.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalupdate.com/interviewmetalblade.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">4 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Show No Mercy</italics><space/>(1983–1984)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/17">Without a recording budget, the band was forced to self-finance its debut album.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/18">Combining the savings of <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link>, who was employed as a<space/><link><target>respiratory therapy</target><part>respiratory therapist</part></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Live Chat with Tom Araya of Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Live Chat with Tom Araya of Slayer</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">ESPguitars.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.espguitars.com/news/news_tomchat.html</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061112194539/http://www.espguitars.com/news/news_tomchat.html</param>\n<param name="archivedate">12 November 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Live Chat with Tom Araya of Slayer</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">ESPguitars.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.espguitars.com/news/news_tomchat.html</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061112194539/http://www.espguitars.com/news/news_tomchat.html</param>\n<param name="archivedate">12 November 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and money borrowed from <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King's</part></link> father,<extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">An exclusive oral history of Slayer</param>\n<param name="publisher">Decibel Magazine</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4566</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20060813155123/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4566</param>\n<param name="archivedate">28 December 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">3 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">An exclusive oral history of Slayer</param>\n<param name="publisher">Decibel Magazine</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4566</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20060813155123/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4566</param>\n<param name="archivedate">28 December 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">3 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>the band entered the studio in November 1983.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/19">The album was rushed into release, hitting shelves three weeks after tracks were completed.</sentence><space/><sentence id="73575/20"><italics><link><target>Show No Mercy</target></link></italics>, released in December 1983 by <link synthetic="true"><target>Metal Blade Records</target></link>, generated underground popularity for the band, and the group began its first national club tour in 1984 to promote the album traveling in <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Dave Lombardo's</part></link><space/><link><target>Camaro</target></link><space/>towing a<space/><link><target>U-Haul</target></link><space/>trailer.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/21">The tour gave the band additional popularity; sales of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Show No Mercy</target></link></italics><space/>reached more than 20,000 in the US and another 20,000 worldwide.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="INTERVIEW WITH BRIAN SLAGEL"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/22">In August 1984, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> released a three song<space/><link><target>extended play</target><part>EP</part></link><space/>titled<space/><italics><link><target>Haunting the Chapel</target></link></italics>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/23">The EP featured a darker, more<space/><link><target>thrash metal</target><part>thrash</part></link>-oriented style than its predecessor, and laid the groundwork for the future direction of the band.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer : Haunting the Chapel"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer:Haunting the Chapel</param>\n<param name="author">Rivadavia, Eduardo</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,164341,00.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer:Haunting the Chapel</param>\n<param name="author">Rivadavia, Eduardo</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/store/artist/album/0,,164341,00.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/24">The opening track, "Chemical Warfare", has become a live staple, played at nearly every show since 1984.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/25">After the release of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Haunting the Chapel</target></link></italics>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> made its live European debut at the<space/><italics>Heavy Sounds <link synthetic="true"><target>Download festival</target><part>Festival</part></link></italics><space/>in<space/><link><target>Belgium</target></link><space/>opening for<space/><link><target>UFO (band)</target><part>UFO</part></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer - Jeff Hanneman"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Lahtinen, Lexi</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">18 December 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&amp;task=view&amp;id=737&amp;Itemid=60</param>\n<param name="accessdate">27 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Lahtinen, Lexi</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">18 December 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&amp;task=view&amp;id=737&amp;Itemid=60</param>\n<param name="accessdate">27 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>returning to the US to begin the<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Haunting the Chapel</target><part>Haunting The</part></link> West Coast</italics><space/>tour.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Dark Angel"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Dark Angel</param>\n<param name="publisher">Voicesfromthedarkside.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/interviews/darkangel2.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">4 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Dark Angel</param>\n<param name="publisher">Voicesfromthedarkside.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/interviews/darkangel2.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">4 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/26">Following the tour, <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> joined<space/><link><target>Dave Mustaine</target></link>'s new band <link synthetic="true"><target>Megadeth</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Megadeth History"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Megadeth History</param>\n<param name="publisher">Megadeth.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.megadeth.com/index.php?section=history</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061119080050/http://www.megadeth.com/index.php?section=history</param>\n<param name="archivedate">19 November 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Megadeth History</param>\n<param name="publisher">Megadeth.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.megadeth.com/index.php?section=history</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061119080050/http://www.megadeth.com/index.php?section=history</param>\n<param name="archivedate">19 November 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/27"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> was worried about <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King's</part></link> decision, stating in an interview, "I guess we’re gonna get a new guitar player.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/28">While <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Mustaine</target><part>Mustaine</part></link> wanted <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> to stay on a permanent basis, <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> left after five shows, stating <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Mustaine</target><part>Mustaine's</part></link> band was "taking too much of my time".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/29">The split caused a rift between <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Mustaine</target><part>Mustaine</part></link>, which evolved into a long running feud between the two bands.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="cocksucker"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=32802</param>\n<param name="title">"Slayer's Kerry King Says Dave Mustaine is 'A Cocksucker'" - February 12, 2005</param>\n<param name="work">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="accessdate">October 21, 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=32802</param>\n<param name="title">"Slayer's Kerry King Says Dave Mustaine is 'A Cocksucker'" - February 12, 2005</param>\n<param name="work">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="accessdate">October 21, 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/30">Following <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King's</part></link> return, the band embarked on the<space/><italics>1984 Combat Tour</italics>, with<space/><link><target>Venom (band)</target><part>Venom</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link>, and released a<space/><link><target>live album</target></link><space/>titled<space/><italics><link><target>Live Undead</target></link></italics><space/>in November.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Hell Awaits</italics><space/>(1985–1986)</heading><paragraph><template name="Listen">\n<param name="filename">Hell Awaits clip.ogg</param>\n<param name="title">"Hell Awaits" (1985)</param>\n<param name="description">"Hell Awaits" features a backwards recording of a demonic voice saying "join us" and "welcome back".</param>\n</template><sentence id="73575/31"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> released its first live<space/><link><target>home video</target></link><space/>in 1985, dubbed<space/><italics>Combat Tour: The Ultimate Revenge</italics>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/32">The video featured live footage filmed at<space/><link><target>New York</target></link>'s<space/><link><target>Studio 54</target></link><space/>club, on the band's 1984 tour with <link synthetic="true"><target>Venom (band)</target><part>Venom</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/33">By early 1985,<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Show No Mercy</target></link></italics><space/>had sold over 40,000 copies,<extension extension_name="ref" name="INTERVIEW WITH BRIAN SLAGEL"/><space/>which led to the band returning to the studio to record a second full length album.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/34"><link synthetic="true"><target>Metal Blade Records</target><part>Metal Blade</part></link> financed a recording budget, which allowed the band to hire producer<space/><link><target>Ron Fair</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/35">Released in September 1985, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> second full length release<space/><italics><link><target>Hell Awaits</target></link></italics><space/>expanded on the darkness of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Haunting the Chapel</target></link></italics>, with<space/><link><target>hell</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Satan</target></link><space/>as common song subjects.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/36">The album was the band's most<space/><link><target>progressive rock</target><part>progressive</part></link><space/>offering, featuring longer and more complex song structures.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/37">The intro of the title track is a<space/><link><target>Backmasking</target><part>backwards recording</part></link><space/>of a demonic-sounding voice repeating "Join us", ending with "Welcome back" before the track begins.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/38">The album was a hit, with fans choosing <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> for best band, best live band,<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Hell Awaits</target></link></italics><space/>as 1985's best album, and <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target></link> as best drummer in the British magazine<space/><italics><link><target>Metal Forces</target></link></italics>' 1985 Readers Poll.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Rockdetector Biography - Years 85 to 86"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Rockdetector Biography - Years 85 to 86</param>\n<param name="author">Sharpe-Young, Garry</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rockdetector.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url">http://www.rockdetector.com/officialbio,8189.sm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2006-12-08</param>\n</template><template name="Dead link">\n<param name="date">October 2010</param>\n<param name="bot">H3llBot</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Rockdetector Biography - Years 85 to 86</param>\n<param name="author">Sharpe-Young, Garry</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rockdetector.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url">http://www.rockdetector.com/officialbio,8189.sm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2006-12-08</param>\n</template><space/><template name="Dead link">\n<param name="date">October 2010</param>\n<param name="bot">H3llBot</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Reign in Blood</italics><space/>(1986–1987)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/39">Following the success of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Hell Awaits</target></link></italics>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> was offered a recording contract with<space/><link><target>Russell Simmons</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Rick Rubin</target></link>'s newly founded<space/><link><target>Def Jam Recordings</target><part>Def Jam Records</part></link>, a largely<space/><link><target>hip hop music</target><part>hip hop</part></link>-based label.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/40">The band accepted and with an experienced producer and<space/><link><target>major label</target></link><space/>recording budget, the band underwent a sonic makeover resulting in shorter, faster songs with clearer production.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/41">Gone were the complex arrangements and long songs featured on<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Hell Awaits</target></link></italics>, ditched in favor of stripped down,<space/><link><target>thrash metal</target></link><space/>influenced song structures.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/42"><link synthetic="true"><target>Def Jam Recordings</target><part>Def Jam's</part></link> distributor,<space/><link><target>Columbia Records</target></link>, refused to release the album<space/><italics><link><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics><space/>due to its graphic cover art and themes.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/43">For example, "<link><target>Angel of Death (song)</target><part>Angel of Death</part></link>" detailed<space/><link><target>The Holocaust</target><part>Holocaust</part></link><space/><link><target>concentration camp</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>and the<space/><link><target>human experiments</target></link><space/>conducted by <link synthetic="true"><target>Nazism</target><part>Nazi</part></link> physician<space/><link><target>Josef Mengele</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/44">The album was distributed by<space/><link><target>Geffen Records</target></link><space/>on October 7, 1986.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/45">However, due to the controversy,<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics><space/>did not appear on <link synthetic="true"><target>Geffen Records</target></link>’ release schedule.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/46">Although the album received virtually no radio airplay, it became the band's first to enter the<space/><link><target>Billboard 200</target></link>, debuting at #94,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Billboard"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's album chart history</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.chartFormatGroupName=Albums&amp;model.vnuArtistId=5692&amp;model.vnuAlbumId=789249</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's album chart history</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.chartFormatGroupName=Albums&amp;model.vnuArtistId=5692&amp;model.vnuAlbumId=789249</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and the band's first album certified gold in the <link synthetic="true"><target>United States</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="RIAA"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/47">In October 1986, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> embarked on the<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target><part>Reign in</part></link> Pain</italics><space/>world tour, with<space/><link><target>Overkill (band)</target><part>Overkill</part></link><space/>in the US, and<space/><link><target>Malice (metal band)</target><part>Malice</part></link><space/>in Europe.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/48">The band was added as the opening act on<space/><link><target>W.A.S.P. (band)</target><part>W.A.S.P.'s</part></link><space/>US tour, but just one month in, drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> left the band: "I wasn't making any money.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/49">I figured if we were gonna be doing this professionally, on a major label, I wanted my rent and utilities paid.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/50">To continue with the tour, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> enlisted<space/><link><target>Tony Scaglione</target></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Whiplash (band)</target><part>Whiplash</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/51">However, <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo's</part></link> wife convinced <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Dave</part></link> to return in 1987.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/52">At the insistence of <link synthetic="true"><target>Rick Rubin</target><part>Rubin</part></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> recorded a<space/><link><target>cover version</target></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Iron Butterfly</target></link>'s "<link><target>In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida (song)</target><part>In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida</part></link>" for the film<space/><italics><link><target>Less Than Zero (film)</target><part>Less Than Zero</part></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/53">Although the band was not happy with the final product, <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> deeming it "a poor representation of <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>" and <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> labeling it "a hunk of shit", it was one of their first songs to garner<space/><link><target>radio airplay</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>South of Heaven</italics><space/>(1988–1989)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/54"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> returned to the studio to record their fourth studio album.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/55">To contrast the speed of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>, the band consciously decided to slow down the<space/><link><target>tempo</target><trail>s</trail></link>, and incorporate more melodic singing.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/56">According to <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link>, "We knew we couldn’t top<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>, so we had to slow down.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/57">We knew whatever we did was gonna be compared to that album, and I remember we actually discussed slowing down.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/58">It was weird—we’ve never done that on an album, before or since.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/></paragraph><paragraph>1988's<space/><sentence id="73575/59"><italics><link><target>South of Heaven</target></link></italics><space/>received mixed responses from both fans and critics, although it was <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> most commercially successful release at the time, debuting at #57 on the<space/><link><target>Billboard 200</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Billboard"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Artist Chart History</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.chartFormatGroupName=Albums&amp;model.vnuArtistId=5692&amp;model.vnuAlbumId=789249</param>\n<param name="accessdate">25 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Artist Chart History</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/retrieve_chart_history.do?model.chartFormatGroupName=Albums&amp;model.vnuArtistId=5692&amp;model.vnuAlbumId=789249</param>\n<param name="accessdate">25 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and the second album to receive gold certification in the <link synthetic="true"><target>United States</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="RIAA"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Recording Industry Association of America Gold &amp;amp; Platinum Searchable Database</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>RIAA</target></link></param>\n<param name="url">http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH</param>\n<param name="accessdate">24 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Recording Industry Association of America Gold &amp;amp; Platinum Searchable Database</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>RIAA</target></link></param>\n<param name="url">http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH</param>\n<param name="accessdate">24 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/60">Press response to the album was mixed, with<space/><italics><link><target>Allmusic</target></link></italics><space/>citing the album as "disturbing and powerful",<extension extension_name="ref" name="South of Heaven"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">South ofs Heaven</param>\n<param name="author">Henderson, Alex</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusicguide.com</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18221</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">South ofs Heaven</param>\n<param name="author">Henderson, Alex</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusicguide.com</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18221</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and Kim Nelly of<space/><italics><link><target>Rolling Stone</target></link></italics><space/>calling it "genuinely offensive satanic drivel".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer - Album Reviews"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Album Reviews</param>\n<param name="author">Neely, Kim</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rolling stone</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/slayer/albums/album/128851/review/5943269/south_of_heaven</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Album Reviews</param>\n<param name="author">Neely, Kim</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rolling stone</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/slayer/albums/album/128851/review/5943269/south_of_heaven</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/61"><link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> said "that album was my most lackluster performance", although <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> called it a "late bloomer" which eventually grew on people.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Seasons in the Abyss</italics><space/>(1990–1993)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/62"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> returned to the studio with co-producer<space/><link><target>Andy Wallace (producer)</target><part>Andy Wallace</part></link><space/>in 1989, to record their fifth studio album.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/63">Following the backlash created by<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>South of Heaven</target></link></italics>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> returned to the "pounding speed of<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>, while retaining their newfound<space/><link><target>melodic</target></link><space/>sense".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="AMGSeasons"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Season in the Abyss AMG album review</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18222</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Season in the Abyss AMG album review</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18222</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/64"><italics><link><target>Seasons in the Abyss</target></link></italics>, released on October 25, 1990, was the first <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> album to be released under <link synthetic="true"><target>Rick Rubin</target><part>Rubin's</part></link> new<space/><link><target>Def American</target></link><space/>label, as he parted ways with <link synthetic="true"><target>Def Jam Recordings</target><part>Def Jam</part></link> owner<space/><link><target>Russell Simmons</target></link><space/>over creative differences.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/65">The album debuted at #44 on the <link synthetic="true"><target>Billboard 200</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Billboard"/><space/>and was certified gold in 1992.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="RIAA"/><space/><sentence id="73575/66">The title track spawned <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> first music video, which was filmed in front of the<space/><link><target>Giza pyramid complex</target><part>Giza pyramids</part></link><space/>in Egypt prior to the<space/><link><target>Gulf War</target></link>.</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/67"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> returned as a live act in September 1990 to co-headline the European<space/><link><target>Clash of the Titans tour</target><part>''Clash of the Titans'' tour</part></link><space/>with<space/><link><target>Megadeth</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Suicidal Tendencies</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Testament (band)</target><part>Testament</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/68">During the sold out European leg of this tour tickets fetched up to 1,000 Deutschmark ($680 USD) on the black market.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/69">With the popularity of <link synthetic="true"><target>American Recordings (US)</target><part>American</part></link> thrash at its peak, the tour was extended to the US beginning in May 1991, with <link synthetic="true"><target>Megadeth</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Anthrax (band)</target><part>Anthrax</part></link><space/>and opening act<space/><link><target>Alice in Chains</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/70">The band released a double live album,<space/><italics><link><target>Decade of Aggression</target></link></italics><space/>in 1991, to celebrate ten years.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/71">The compilation debuted at #55 on the <link synthetic="true"><target>Billboard 200</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Billboard"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/72">In May 1992, <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> quit the band due to conflicts with other members, as well as arguments over his wish to bring his wife on tour.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Meet the new Slayer, same as the old Slayer'l"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Meet the new Slayer, same as the old Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Patrizio, Andy</param>\n<param name="publisher">IGN</param>\n<param name="date">14 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://au.music.ign.com/articles/725/725459p1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Meet the new Slayer, same as the old Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Patrizio, Andy</param>\n<param name="publisher">IGN</param>\n<param name="date">14 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://au.music.ign.com/articles/725/725459p1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/73"><link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> formed his own band<space/><link><target>Grip Inc</target></link>, with<space/><link><target>Voodoocult</target></link><space/>guitarist<space/><link><target>Waldemar Sorychta</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Waldemar Sorychta interview"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Waldemar Sorychta interview</param>\n<param name="publisher">antenna.nu</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.antenna.nu/gripinc/interview1.php</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Waldemar Sorychta interview</param>\n<param name="publisher">antenna.nu</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.antenna.nu/gripinc/interview1.php</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> recruited former<space/><link><target>Forbidden (band)</target><part>Forbidden</part></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Paul Bostaph</target></link><space/>to fill his place.Slayer made its debut appearance with <link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph</part></link> at the 1992<space/><link><target>Monsters of Rock#1992</target><part>Monsters of Rock</part></link><space/>festival at<space/><link><target>Castle Donington</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/74"><link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph's</part></link> first studio effort was a medley of three<space/><link><target>Exploited</target></link><space/>songs, "<link synthetic="true"><target>war</target><part>War</part></link>", "UK '82", and "<link synthetic="true"><target>Vision of Disorder</target><part>Disorder</part></link>", with rapper<space/><link><target>Ice T</target></link>, for the<space/><italics><link><target>Judgment Night (film)</target><part>Judgment Night</part></link></italics><space/>movie soundtrack in 1993.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Legendary rapper and longtime metal advocate moves on with the Body Count"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Legendary rapper and longtime metal advocate moves on with the Body Count</param>\n<param name="author">Bennett, J</param>\n<param name="publisher">Decibelmagazine.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url">http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4908</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061020204850/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4908</param>\n<param name="archivedate">20 October 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">27 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Legendary rapper and longtime metal advocate moves on with the Body Count</param>\n<param name="author">Bennett, J</param>\n<param name="publisher">Decibelmagazine.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="url">http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4908</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061020204850/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features_detail.aspx?id=4908</param>\n<param name="archivedate">20 October 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">27 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Divine Intervention</italics><space/>(1994–1995)</heading><paragraph><template name="Listen">\n<param name="filename">Slayer_SS3_clip.ogg</param>\n<param name="title">"SS-3" (1994)</param>\n<param name="description">"SS-3" is about Reinhard Heydrich, an architect of the Holocaust. SS-3 refers to the license plate number of the car in which he was killed.</param>\n</template><sentence id="73575/75">In 1994, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> released<space/><italics><link><target>Divine Intervention (album)</target><part>Divine Intervention</part></link></italics>, the band's first record with drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/76">The record became the band's highest charting at that time, peaking at #8 on the <link synthetic="true"><target>Billboard 200</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/77"><link synthetic="true"><target>Divine Intervention (album)</target><part>Divine Intervention</part></link> was certified gold.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Billboard"/><space/><sentence id="73575/78">The album featured songs about<space/><link><target>Reinhard Heydrich</target></link>, an architect of the <link synthetic="true"><target>The Holocaust</target><part>Holocaust</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Jeffrey Dahmer</target></link>, of apartment number "213", where he murdered, raped, and tortured seventeen victims.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/79">Other themes included murder, the evils of church, and the lengths to which governments will go to wield power, <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya's</part></link> interest in serial killers inspired much of the content of the lyrics.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Live Chat with Tom Araya of Slayer"/><extension extension_name="ref" name="Divine Intervention - Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Divine Intervention - Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Henderson, Alex</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r203780</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">21 June 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Divine Intervention - Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Henderson, Alex</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r203780</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">21 June 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/80"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> geared up for a world tour in 1995, with openers<space/><link><target>Biohazard (band)</target><part>Biohazard</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Machine Head (band)</target><part>Machine Head</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/81">A video of concert footage,<space/><italics><link><target>Live Intrusion</target></link></italics><space/>was released, featuring a joint<space/><link><target>cover song</target><part>cover</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Venom (band)</target><part>Venom's</part></link><space/>"Witching Hour" with <link synthetic="true"><target>Machine Head (band)</target><part>Machine Head</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/82">Relations between <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Machine Head (band)</target><part>Machine Head</part></link> have since badly deteriorated.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Machine head diary, 2004"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Machine head diary, 2004</param>\n<param name="author"><link><target>Robert Flynn</target></link></param>\n<param name="publisher">Machinehead1.com</param>\n<param name="date">29 April 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.machinehead1.com/diary_2004.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Machine head diary, 2004</param>\n<param name="author"><link><target>Robert Flynn</target></link></param>\n<param name="publisher">Machinehead1.com</param>\n<param name="date">29 April 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.machinehead1.com/diary_2004.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/83">Following the tour, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> were billed third at the 1995<space/><link><target>Monsters of Rock</target></link><space/>festival, headlined by<space/><link><target>Metallica</target></link>.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Undisputed Attitude</italics><space/>(1996–1997)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/84">In 1996,<space/><italics><link><target>Undisputed Attitude</target></link></italics>, an album of<space/><link><target>Punk rock</target><part>punk</part></link><space/><link><target>cover version</target><part>covers</part></link>, was released.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/85">The band covered songs by<space/><link><target>Minor Threat</target></link>,<space/><link><target>TSOL</target><part>T.S.O.L.</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Dirty Rotten Imbeciles</target><part>D.R.I.</part></link>,<space/><link><target>D.I. (band)</target><part>D.I.</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Verbal Abuse</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Dr. Know (band)</target><part>Dr. Know</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>The Stooges</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/86">The album featured three original tracks, "Gemini", "Can't Stand You", "Ddamm"; the latter two were written by <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> in 1984–1985 for a side project entitled Pap Smear.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/87"><link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph</part></link> left <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> shortly after the album's release to work on his own project,<space/><link><target>The Truth About Seafood</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/88">With <link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph's</part></link> departure, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> recruited<space/><link><target>Testament (band)</target><part>Testament</part></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Jon Dette</target></link>, and headlined the 1996 <link synthetic="true"><target>Ozzfest</target></link> alongside<space/><link><target>Ozzy Osbourne</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Danzig (band)</target><part>Danzig</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Biohazard (band)</target><part>Biohazard</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Sepultura</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Fear Factory</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/89"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jon Dette</target><part>Dette</part></link> was fired after a year, due to a fallout with band members; <link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph</part></link> returned to continue the tour.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Jon Dette has left Slayer and is being replaced by Paul Bostaph!"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Jon Dette has left Slayer and is being replaced by Paul Bostaph!</param>\n<param name="author">Hellqvist, Janek</param>\n<param name="publisher">Slaytanic.com</param>\n<param name="date">27 January 1997</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.slaytanic.com/news.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Jon Dette has left Slayer and is being replaced by Paul Bostaph!</param>\n<param name="author">Hellqvist, Janek</param>\n<param name="publisher">Slaytanic.com</param>\n<param name="date">27 January 1997</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.slaytanic.com/news.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/90">A lawsuit was brought against the band in 1996, by the parents of<space/><link><target>Elyse Pahler</target></link>, who accused the band of encouraging their daughter's murderers through their lyrics.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="The Elyse Marie Pahler Foundation, In Memory of Our Loving Daughter"/><space/><sentence id="73575/91"><link synthetic="true"><target>Elyse Pahler</target><part>Elyse</part></link> was drugged, strangled, stabbed, trampled on, and raped as a<space/><link><target>sacrifice</target></link><space/>to the devil by three fans of the band.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="The Elyse Marie Pahler Foundation, In Memory of Our Loving Daughter"/><space/><sentence id="73575/92">The case was unsealed by the court on May 19, 2000, stating <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> and related business markets distribute harmful products to teens, encouraging violent acts through their lyrics,<extension extension_name="ref" name="The Elyse Marie Pahler Foundation, In Memory of Our Loving Daughter"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The Elyse Marie Pahler Foundation, In Memory of Our Loving Daughter</param>\n<param name="publisher">elysemarie.org</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.elysemarie.org/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The Elyse Marie Pahler Foundation, In Memory of Our Loving Daughter</param>\n<param name="publisher">elysemarie.org</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.elysemarie.org/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and "none of the vicious crimes committed against <link synthetic="true"><target>Elyse Pahler</target><part>Elyse</part></link> Marie <link synthetic="true"><target>Elyse Pahler</target><part>Pahler</part></link> would have occurred without the intentional marketing strategy of the death-metal band <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer named in lawsuit"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer named in lawsuit</param>\n<param name="publisher">Guardian</param>\n<param name="date">24 January 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://fradical.com/slayer_named_in_lawsuit.htm</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071014204909/http://fradical.com/slayer_named_in_lawsuit.htm</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 October 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer named in lawsuit</param>\n<param name="publisher">Guardian</param>\n<param name="date">24 January 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://fradical.com/slayer_named_in_lawsuit.htm</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071014204909/http://fradical.com/slayer_named_in_lawsuit.htm</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 October 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/93">The lawsuit was dismissed in 2001, for multiple reasons including "principles of free speech, lack of a duty and lack of foreseeability".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer: Out Of The Dock"/><space/><sentence id="73575/94">A second lawsuit was filed by the parents, an amended complaint for damages against <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>, their label, and other industry and label entities.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/95">The lawsuit was dismissed; Judge E.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/96"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeffrey Dahmer</target><part>Jeffrey</part></link> Burke stated, "I do not consider <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> music obscene, indecent or harmful to minors.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer: Out Of The Dock"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: Out Of The Dock</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Metal Hammer</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">31 October 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/?id=39564</param>\n<param name="accessdate">15 October 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: Out Of The Dock</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Metal Hammer</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">31 October 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/?id=39564</param>\n<param name="accessdate">15 October 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Diabolus in Musica</italics><space/>(1998–2000)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/97"><italics><link><target>Diabolus in Musica</target></link></italics><space/>(Latin for "The Devil in <link synthetic="true"><target>Sony Music Entertainment</target><part>Music</part></link>")<extension extension_name="ref" name="Diabolus in Musica, The Tritone of Musick"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Diabolus in Musica, The Tritone of Musick</param>\n<param name="author">Cherubim, David</param>\n<param name="publisher">Thelemicmusick.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://thelemicmusick.net/davidcherubim/tritone.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Diabolus in Musica, The Tritone of Musick</param>\n<param name="author">Cherubim, David</param>\n<param name="publisher">Thelemicmusick.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://thelemicmusick.net/davidcherubim/tritone.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>was released in 1998, and debuted at #31 on the <link synthetic="true"><target>Billboard 200</target></link>, selling over 46,000 copies.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer: 'Christ Illusion' Lands At No. 5 On BILLBOARD Chart!"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: 'Christ Illusion' lands at No. 5 on Billboard chart!</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">16 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=56559</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: 'Christ Illusion' lands at No. 5 on Billboard chart!</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">16 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=56559</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/98">The album received a mixed critical reception and was criticized for adopting characteristics of<space/><link><target>nu metal</target></link><space/>music such as tuned down guitars, murky chord structures, and churning beats.</sentence><space/><sentence id="73575/99"><italics>Blabbermouth.net</italics><space/>reviewer Borijov Krgin described the album as "a feeble attempt at incorporating updated elements into the group's sound, the presence of which elevated the band's efforts somewhat and offered hope that <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> could refrain from endlessly rehashing their previous material for their future output",<extension extension_name="ref" name="Blabbermouth Review"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer God Hates Us All (American)</param>\n<param name="author">Krgin, Borivoj</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=50</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 May 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer God Hates Us All (American)</param>\n<param name="author">Krgin, Borivoj</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/showreview.aspx?reviewID=50</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 May 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>while<space/><italics><link><target>New York Times</target></link></italics>' Ben Ratliff had similar sentiments by saying: "Eight of the 11 songs on<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Diabolus in Musica</target></link>,</italics><space/>a few of which were played at the show, are in the same gray key, and the band's rhythmic ideas have a wearying sameness too.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="NYTReview"><template name="cite news">\n<param name="last">Ratliff</param>\n<param name="first">Ben</param>\n<param name="title">It's a Major Metal Band, and Even the Furniture Isn't Safe</param>\n<param name="work"><link><target>The New York Times</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">22 June 1998</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/22/arts/pop-review-it-s-a-major-metal-band-and-even-the-furniture-isn-t-safe.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate"/>\n</template><template name="cite news">\n<param name="last">Ratliff</param>\n<param name="first">Ben</param>\n<param name="title">It's a Major Metal Band, and Even the Furniture Isn't Safe</param>\n<param name="work"><link><target>The New York Times</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">22 June 1998</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.nytimes.com/1998/06/22/arts/pop-review-it-s-a-major-metal-band-and-even-the-furniture-isn-t-safe.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate"/>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/100">The album was the band's first to primarily feature dropped tuning, as featured on the lead track, "Bitter Peace" (<template name="Audio">\n<param name="1">Slayer_Bitter_Peace.ogg</param>\n<param name="2">sample</param>\n</template>), making use of the<space/><link><target>tritone</target></link><space/>interval referred to in the Middle Ages as the Devil's interval.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="The Devil's Music"><template name="cite news">\n<param name="title">The Devil's Music</param>\n<param name="author">Rohrer, Finlo</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n<param name="date">28 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/4952646.stm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite news">\n<param name="title">The Devil's Music</param>\n<param name="author">Rohrer, Finlo</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n<param name="date">28 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/4952646.stm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/101"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> teamed up with<space/><link><target>digital hardcore</target></link><space/>group<space/><link><target>Atari Teenage Riot</target></link><space/>to record a song for the<space/><italics><link><target>Spawn (film)</target><part>Spawn</part></link></italics><space/>soundtrack titled "No Remorse (I Wanna Die)".</sentence> <sentence id="73575/102">The band later paid tribute to<space/><link><target>Black Sabbath</target></link><space/>by recording a cover of "Hand of Doom" for the second of two tribute albums, entitled<space/><italics><link><target>Nativity in Black II</target></link>.</italics><space/>A world tour followed to support the new album, with <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> making an appearance at the <link synthetic="true"><target>United States</target><part>United</part></link> Kingdom<space/><link><target>Ozzfest#1996-1998: Early years</target><part>Ozzfest 1998</part></link><space/>alongside<space/><link><target>Black Sabbath</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Ozzy Osbourne</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Foo Fighters</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Pantera</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Soulfly</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Fear Factory</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Therapy?</target></link>.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>God Hates Us All</italics><space/>(2001–2005)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/103">After delays regarding remixing and artwork,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer Nails Down Release Date For 'God'"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer Nails Down Release Date For 'God'</param>\n<param name="author">Weiss, Neal</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo Music</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">7 June 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12056099</param>\n<param name="accessdate">26 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer Nails Down Release Date For 'God'</param>\n<param name="author">Weiss, Neal</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo Music</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">7 June 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12056099</param>\n<param name="accessdate">26 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>including slip covers created to cover the original artwork as it was deemed "too graphic",<space/><italics><link><target>God Hates Us All</target></link></italics><space/>was released on<space/><link><target>September 11, 2001</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/104">The band received its first<space/><link><target>Grammy</target></link><space/>nomination for the lead track "Disciple", although the <link synthetic="true"><target>Grammy Award</target><part>Grammy</part></link> was awarded to<space/><link><target>Tool (band)</target><part>Tool</part></link>, for "<link><target>Schism (song)</target><part>Schism</part></link>".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name=" 44th Grammy Awards - 2002"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">44th Grammy Awards - 2002</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rockonthenet.com</param>\n<param name="date">27 February 2002</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2002/grammys.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">44th Grammy Awards - 2002</param>\n<param name="publisher">Rockonthenet.com</param>\n<param name="date">27 February 2002</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2002/grammys.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/105">The September 11th attack on America jeopardized the 2001 European tour<space/><italics>Tattoo the Planet</italics><space/>originally set to feature<space/><link><target>Pantera</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Static X</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Biohazard (band)</target><part>Biohazard</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Vision of Disorder</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/106">Dates were canceled or postponed due to flight restrictions, with a majority of bands deciding to withdraw, leaving <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Static X</target></link> remaining for the European leg of the tour.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Tattoo The Planet Officially Postponed"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Tattoo The Planet officially postponed</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">13 October 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111046&amp;resource=111046&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071114113713/http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111046&amp;resource=111046&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 November 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Tattoo The Planet officially postponed</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">13 October 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111046&amp;resource=111046&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071114113713/http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111046&amp;resource=111046&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 November 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/107"><link synthetic="true"><target>Pantera</target></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Vision of Disorder</target></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Biohazard (band)</target><part>Biohazard</part></link> were replaced by<space/><link><target>Cradle of Filth</target></link><space/>and other bands dependent on location;<space/><link><target>Amorphis</target></link>,<space/><link><target>In Flames</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Moonspell</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Children of Bodom</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Necrodeath</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/108">The Birmingham, England date on the tour though only featured <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Biohazard (band)</target><part>Biohazard</part></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Cradle of Filth</target></link> and Raging Speedhorn due to <link synthetic="true"><target>Static X</target></link> pulling out over previous commitments, instead playing their scheduled dates in Germany.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/109">Drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Paul Bostaph</target><part>Bostaph</part></link> left <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> before Christmas in 2001, due to a chronic elbow injury which would hinder his ability to play.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer:"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: Lombardo's back!</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">3 January 2002</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111297&amp;resource=111297&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071114113718/http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111297&amp;resource=111297&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 November 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: Lombardo's back!</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">3 January 2002</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111297&amp;resource=111297&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20071114113718/http://www.kerrang.com/nav?page=kerrang.reviews.artist.news&amp;fixture_news=111297&amp;resource=111297&amp;fixture_artist=149178</param>\n<param name="archivedate">14 November 2007</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/110"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> "<link synthetic="true"><target>God Hates Us All</target></link>" tour was unfinished so <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> contacted original drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link>, and asked if he would like to finish the remainder of the tour.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/111"><link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> accepted the offer, and stayed as a permanent member.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer:"/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/112"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> toured playing<space/><italics><link><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics><space/>in its entirety throughout the fall of 2003, under the tour banner "<link synthetic="true"><target>Still Reigning</target></link>".</sentence> <sentence id="73575/113">Their playing of the final song "<link><target>Raining Blood</target></link>" culminated with the band drenched in a rain of stage blood.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/114"><link synthetic="true"><target>live album</target><part>Live</part></link> footage of this was recorded at the <link synthetic="true"><target>Augusta, Maine</target><part>Augusta</part></link> Civic Center in<space/><link><target>Augusta, Maine</target></link>, on July 11, 2004 and released on the 2004 DVD<space/><italics><link><target>Still Reigning</target></link></italics>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/115">The band also released<space/><italics><link><target>War at the Warfield</target></link></italics><space/>and a box set,<space/><italics><link><target>Soundtrack to the Apocalypse</target></link></italics><space/>featuring rarities, live CD and DVD performances and various <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> paraphernalia.</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/116">From 2002 to 2004 the band performed over 250 tour dates, headlining major music festivals including H82k2, Summer tour,<space/><link><target>Ozzfest#2000-2006: Commercial success</target><part>Ozzfest 2004</part></link><space/>and a European tour with<space/><link><target>Slipknot (band)</target><part>Slipknot</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/117">While preparing for the <link synthetic="true"><target>Download festival</target><part>Download Festival</part></link> in England,<space/><link><target>Metallica</target></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Lars Ulrich</target></link><space/>was rushed to hospital with a mysterious illness, and was unable to perform.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Metallica's Lars Ulrich Hospitalized In Switzerland, Misses Show"/><space/><sentence id="73575/118"><link synthetic="true"><target>Metallica</target></link> vocalist<space/><link><target>James Hetfield</target></link><space/>searched for volunteers at the last minute to replace <link synthetic="true"><target>Lars Ulrich</target><part>Ulrich</part></link>; <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Slipknot (band)</target><part>Slipknot</part></link> drummer<space/><link><target>Joey Jordison</target></link><space/>volunteered, with <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> performing the songs "<link><target>Battery (song)</target><part>Battery</part></link>" and "<link><target>Kill 'Em All</target><part>The Four Horsemen</part></link>".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Metallica's Lars Ulrich Hospitalized In Switzerland, Misses Show"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Metallica's Lars Ulrich Hospitalized In Switzerland, Misses Show</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo Music</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">7 June 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054238</param>\n<param name="accessdate">9 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Metallica's Lars Ulrich Hospitalized In Switzerland, Misses Show</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo Music</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">7 June 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054238</param>\n<param name="accessdate">9 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>Christ Illusion</italics><space/>(2006–2008)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/119">The album<space/><italics><link><target>Christ Illusion</target></link></italics><space/>was originally scheduled for release on June 6, 2006, and would be the first album with original drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> since 1990's<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Seasons in the Abyss</target></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="KingUltimateGuitar"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's Kerry King: The Art Of Writing Songs That Nobody Else Can Write</param>\n<param name="author">Matera, Joe</param>\n<param name="publisher">UltimateGuitar.com</param>\n<param name="date">4 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/slayers_kerry_king_the_art_of_writing_songs_that_nobody_else_can_write.html?200608041041</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061215152912/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/slayers_kerry_king_the_art_of_writing_songs_that_nobody_else_can_write.html?200608041041</param>\n<param name="archivedate">15 December 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's Kerry King: The Art Of Writing Songs That Nobody Else Can Write</param>\n<param name="author">Matera, Joe</param>\n<param name="publisher">UltimateGuitar.com</param>\n<param name="date">4 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/slayers_kerry_king_the_art_of_writing_songs_that_nobody_else_can_write.html?200608041041</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061215152912/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/slayers_kerry_king_the_art_of_writing_songs_that_nobody_else_can_write.html?200608041041</param>\n<param name="archivedate">15 December 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/120">However, the band decided to delay the release of the record as they did not want to be among the many, according to <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link>, "half-ass, stupid fucking loser bands" releasing records on June 6,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer Recount VENOM 'Pissing' Incident"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer Recount Venom 'Pissing' incident</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">25 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=54174</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer Recount Venom 'Pissing' incident</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">25 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=54174</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>although<space/><italics><link><target>USA Today</target></link></italics><space/>reported the idea was thwarted because the band failed to secure sufficient studio recording time.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Petrecca"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Marketers hope 666 will be their lucky number</param>\n<param name="author">Petrecca, Laura</param>\n<param name="publisher">USAToday.com</param>\n<param name="date">2 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.usatoday.com/money/media/2006-05-31-omen-marketing-usat_x.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Marketers hope 666 will be their lucky number</param>\n<param name="author">Petrecca, Laura</param>\n<param name="publisher">USAToday.com</param>\n<param name="date">2 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.usatoday.com/money/media/2006-05-31-omen-marketing-usat_x.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/121">Instead, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> released<space/><italics><link><target>Eternal Pyre</target></link></italics><space/>on June 6 as a limited-edition<space/><link><target>extended play</target><part>EP</part></link>.</sentence><space/><sentence id="73575/122"><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Eternal Pyre</target></link></italics><space/>featured the song "Cult", a live performance of "<link synthetic="true"><target>war</target><part>War</part></link> Ensemble" in Germany, video footage of the band recording "Cult", and a five minute video of a <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> fan carving the band's name onto his forearm.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/123">Five thousand copies were released and sold exclusively through<space/><link><target>Hot Topic</target></link><space/>chain stores, and sold out within hours of release.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="'Eternal Pyre"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Eternal Pyre</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">17 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=53810</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Eternal Pyre</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">17 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=53810</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/124">On June 30,<space/><link><target>Nuclear Blast Records</target></link><space/>released a 7" vinyl picture disc version limited to a thousand copies.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer: 'Eternal Pyre' 7 Vinyl Picture-Disc Single To Be Released This Month"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: 'Eternal Pyre' 7" Vinyl Picture-Disc Single To Be Released This Month</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">27 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=53810</param>\n<param name="accessdate">15 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer: 'Eternal Pyre' 7" Vinyl Picture-Disc Single To Be Released This Month</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">27 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=53810</param>\n<param name="accessdate">15 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/125"><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Christ Illusion</target></link></italics><space/>was released on August 8, 2006, and debuted at #5 on the<space/><link><target>Billboard 200</target><part>''Billboard'' 200</part></link>, selling over 62,000 copies in its first week.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer's 'Christ Illusion' Is Band's Highest-Ever Billboard Chart Debut Entering at #5"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's "Christ Illusion" Is Band's Highest-Ever Billboard Chart Debut Entering at #5</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">16 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://biz.yahoo.com/iw/060816/0154755.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="dead link">\n<param name="date">November 2008</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's "Christ Illusion" Is Band's Highest-Ever Billboard Chart Debut Entering at #5</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Yahoo</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">16 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://biz.yahoo.com/iw/060816/0154755.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="dead link">\n<param name="date">November 2008</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/126">The album became <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> highest charting, improving on its previous highest charting album,<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Divine Intervention (album)</target><part>Divine Intervention</part></link></italics>, which had debuted at #8.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/127">However, despite its high positioning, the album dropped to #44 in the following week.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Metal, Rock and Alternative Music Doing Well In Billboard"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Metal, Rock and Alternative Music Doing Well In Billboard</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalunderground.com</param>\n<param name="date">23 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=21264</param>\n<param name="accessdate">25 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Metal, Rock and Alternative Music Doing Well In Billboard</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalunderground.com</param>\n<param name="date">23 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=21264</param>\n<param name="accessdate">25 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/128">Three weeks after the album's release <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> were inducted into the<space/><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link><space/>Hall of Fame for their influence to the heavy metal scene.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Lostprophets scoop rock honours"><template name="cite news">\n<param name="title">Lostprophets scoop rock honours</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n<param name="date">25 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5282780.stm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite news">\n<param name="title">Lostprophets scoop rock honours</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n<param name="date">25 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5282780.stm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/129"><link><target>File:Slayerunholy.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>250px</part><part>Slayer performing at ''<link><target>The Unholy Alliance Tour</target></link>'' in October 2006</part></link>A worldwide tour dubbed<space/><italics><link><target>The Unholy Alliance Tour</target></link></italics>, was undertaken to support the new record.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/130">The tour was originally set to launch on June 6, but was postponed to June 10, as <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> had to undergo<space/><link><target>gall bladder</target></link><space/>surgery.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer Frontman Undergoes Gallbladder Surgery, Band Reschedule Early 'Unholy Alliance' Dates"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer frontman undergoes gallbladder surgery, Band Reschedule Early 'Unholy Alliance' Dates</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">10 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrhttp://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Slayer&amp;action=editunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=52111</param>\n<param name="accessdate">9 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer frontman undergoes gallbladder surgery, Band Reschedule Early 'Unholy Alliance' Dates</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">10 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrhttp://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Slayer&amp;action=editunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=52111</param>\n<param name="accessdate">9 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/131"><link><target>In Flames</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Mastodon (band)</target><part>Mastodon</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Children of Bodom</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Lamb of God (band)</target><part>Lamb of God</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Thine Eyes Bleed</target></link><space/>(featuring <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya's</part></link> brother,<space/><link><target>Johnny Araya</target><part>Johnny</part></link>) and Ted Maul (London Hammersmith Apollo) were supporting <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer's 'Unholy Alliance' tour grows"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's 'Unholy Alliance' tour grows</param>\n<param name="author">Zahlaway, Jon</param>\n<param name="publisher">Livedaily.com</param>\n<param name="date">31 March 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.livedaily.com/news/Slayers_Unholy_Alliance_tour_grows-9852.html?t=1</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's 'Unholy Alliance' tour grows</param>\n<param name="author">Zahlaway, Jon</param>\n<param name="publisher">Livedaily.com</param>\n<param name="date">31 March 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.livedaily.com/news/Slayers_Unholy_Alliance_tour_grows-9852.html?t=1</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/132">The tour made its way through America and Europe and the bands who participated, apart from <link synthetic="true"><target>Thine Eyes Bleed</target></link>, reunited to perform at<space/><link><target>Japan</target></link>'s<space/><link><target>Loudpark Festival</target></link><space/>on October 15, 2006.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Loud Park 2006 Unholy Alliance Stage"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Loud Park 2006 Unholy Alliance Stage</param>\n<param name="publisher">Loudpark.com</param>\n<param name="date">4 September 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.loudpark.com/artist.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">24 December 2006</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061117031716/http://www.loudpark.com/artist.html</param>\n<param name="archivedate">17 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Loud Park 2006 Unholy Alliance Stage</param>\n<param name="publisher">Loudpark.com</param>\n<param name="date">4 September 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.loudpark.com/artist.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">24 December 2006</param>\n<param name="archiveurl">http://web.archive.org/web/20061117031716/http://www.loudpark.com/artist.html</param>\n<param name="archivedate">17 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/133">The video for the album's first single, "<link><target>Eyes of the Insane</target></link>", was released on October 30, 2006.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Eyes_of_the_Insane"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer release video for "Eyes Of the Insane"</param>\n<param name="publisher">Punknews.org</param>\n<param name="date">30 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.punknews.org/article/20607</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer release video for "Eyes Of the Insane"</param>\n<param name="publisher">Punknews.org</param>\n<param name="date">30 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.punknews.org/article/20607</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/134">The track was featured on the<space/><italics><link><target>Saw III</target></link></italics><space/>soundtrack, and won a <link synthetic="true"><target>Grammy Award</target><part>Grammy</part></link>-award for "<link><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link>" at the 49th <link synthetic="true"><target>Grammy Award</target><part>Grammy Awards</part></link>, although the band were unable to attend due to touring obligations.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer Wins GRAMMY In 'Best Metal Performance' Category "><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer wins Grammy in 'Best Metal Performance' Category</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">11 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66845</param>\n<param name="accessdate">12 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer wins Grammy in 'Best Metal Performance' Category</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">11 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66845</param>\n<param name="accessdate">12 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/135">A week later, the band visited the 52nd Services Squadron located on the Spangdahlem U.S.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/136">Air <link synthetic="true"><target>Metal Forces</target><part>Force</part></link> Base in Germany to meet and play a show.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/137">This was the first visit ever to a military base for the band.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer To Visit U.S. Troops; U.S"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer To Visit U.S. Troops; U.S</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">31 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=61345</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer To Visit U.S. Troops; U.S</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">31 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=61345</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/138">The band made its first<space/><link><target>network TV</target></link><space/>appearance on the show<space/><italics><link><target>Jimmy Kimmel Live!</target></link></italics><space/>on January 19, playing the song "<link synthetic="true"><target>Eyes of the Insane</target></link>", and four additional songs for fans after the show (although footage from "<link><target>Jihad (song)</target><part>Jihad</part></link>" was cut due to its controversial lyrical themes).</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer On 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!': 'Eyes Of The Insane' Performance Posted Online"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!': 'Eyes Of The Insane' performance posted online</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">20 January 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=65652</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live!': 'Eyes Of The Insane' performance posted online</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">20 January 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=65652</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/139"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> toured Australia and <link synthetic="true"><target>New York</target><part>New</part></link> Zealand in <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> with <link synthetic="true"><target>Mastodon (band)</target><part>Mastodon</part></link>, and appeared at the<space/><link><target>Download Festival</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Rock Am Ring</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer, MARILYN MANSON, KILLSWITCH ENGAGE Confirmed For U.K.'s DOWNLOAD Festival"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer, Marilyn Manson, Killswitch Engage confirmed For UK's Download Festival</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">13 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66979</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer, Marilyn Manson, Killswitch Engage confirmed For UK's Download Festival</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">13 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66979</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and a Summer tour with<space/><link><target>Marilyn Manson (band)</target><part>Marilyn Manson</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Bleeding Through</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="SMASHING PUMPKINS, MARILYN MANSON, Slayer Confirmed For Switzerland's GREENFIELD FESTIVAL"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Smashing Pumpkins, Marilyn Manson, Slayer Confirmed For Switzerland's Greenfield Festival</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">6 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66565</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Smashing Pumpkins, Marilyn Manson, Slayer Confirmed For Switzerland's Greenfield Festival</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">6 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=66565</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/140">The band released a special edition of<space/><italics><link><target>Christ Illusion</target></link></italics>, which featured new cover art and bonus track, "Final Six", which was given a<space/><link><target>Grammy Award</target></link><space/>for "<link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link>".</sentence> <sentence id="73575/141">This is the band's second consecutive award in that category.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="3"><italics>World Painted Blood</italics><space/>(2009–2011)</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/142">In interviews with <link synthetic="true"><target>Thrash metal</target><part>Thrash</part></link> Hits and<space/><italics>Worcester</italics><space/>magazine, <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> states uncertainty with the future of the band,<extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.thrashhits.com/2008/07/slayer-reign-of-fear/</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer: Reign of Fear</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 July 2008</param>\n<param name="author">McIver, Joel</param>\n<param name="authorlink">Joel McIver</param>\n<param name="date">18 July 2008</param>\n<param name="work">Interview with Tom Araya</param>\n<param name="publisher">Thrash Hits</param>\n<param name="quote"/>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.thrashhits.com/2008/07/slayer-reign-of-fear/</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer: Reign of Fear</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 July 2008</param>\n<param name="author">McIver, Joel</param>\n<param name="authorlink">Joel McIver</param>\n<param name="date">18 July 2008</param>\n<param name="work">Interview with Tom Araya</param>\n<param name="publisher">Thrash Hits</param>\n<param name="quote"/>\n</template></extension><space/>and that he could not see himself continuing the career at a later age.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/143">Once the band finished<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>World Painted Blood</target></link></italics>, which was the final record in their contract, the band would sit down and discuss its future.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="LastofSlayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">End of Slayer?</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">ultimate-guitar</param>\n<param name="date">7 August 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/the_end_of_slayer.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">8 August 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">End of Slayer?</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">ultimate-guitar</param>\n<param name="date">7 August 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/the_end_of_slayer.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">8 August 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/144"><link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> was optimistic that the band would produce at least another two records before considering a split: "We're talking of going in the studio next February [2009] and getting the next record out so if we do things in a timely manner I don't see there's any reason why we can't have more than one album out...</sentence> <sentence id="73575/145">I think the time's gonna come when somebody just says: 'I'm done.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/146">I don't wanna do this any more.'</sentence> <sentence id="73575/147">But I'm having a blast.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref"><link type="external" href="http://thequietus.com/articles/00661-slayer-we-could-thrash-out-two-more-albums-if-we-re-fast-enough">Slayer: We Could Thrash Out Two More Albums If We're Fast Enough...</link>, interview with John Doran on The Quietus (2008-11-05)</extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/148"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>, along with<space/><link><target>Trivium (band)</target><part>Trivium</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Mastodon (band)</target><part>Mastodon</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Amon Amarth</target></link><space/>teamed up for a European tour titled '<link synthetic="true"><target>The Unholy Alliance Tour</target><part>The Unholy Alliance</part></link>: Chapter <link synthetic="true"><target>Metal Massacre#Metal Massacre III – 1983</target><part>III</part></link>', throughout October and November 2008.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="'The Unholy Alliance: Chapter III' UK Dates Added"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">'The Unholy Alliance: Chapter III' UK Dates Added</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">11 June 2008</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=98808</param>\n<param name="accessdate">12 June 2008</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">'The Unholy Alliance: Chapter III' UK Dates Added</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">11 June 2008</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=98808</param>\n<param name="accessdate">12 June 2008</param>\n</template></extension><extension extension_name="ref" name="SLAYER's TOM ARAYA Says The Three New Songs 'Kinda Came Together'"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">SLAYER's TOM ARAYA Says The Three New Songs 'Kinda Came Together</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">22 November 2008</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=109448</param>\n<param name="accessdate">14 February 2009</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">SLAYER's TOM ARAYA Says The Three New Songs 'Kinda Came Together</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">22 November 2008</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=109448</param>\n<param name="accessdate">14 February 2009</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/149">On January 27, it was confirmed that <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> will be headlining the second<space/><link><target>Mayhem Festival</target></link><space/>in the summer of 2009.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="press release"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.mayhemfest.com/2009-press-release.pdf</param>\n<param name="title">Mayhem Festival Press Release</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 January 2009</param>\n<param name="work">Mayhemfest.com</param>\n<param name="date">28 January 2009</param>\n</template><template name="Dead link">\n<param name="date">October 2010</param>\n<param name="bot">H3llBot</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.mayhemfest.com/2009-press-release.pdf</param>\n<param name="title">Mayhem Festival Press Release</param>\n<param name="accessdate">28 January 2009</param>\n<param name="work">Mayhemfest.com</param>\n<param name="date">28 January 2009</param>\n</template><space/><template name="Dead link">\n<param name="date">October 2010</param>\n<param name="bot">H3llBot</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/150"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> along with<space/><link><target>Megadeth</target></link><space/>also co-headlined Canadian Carnage, the first time they performed together in more than 15 years when they co-headlined four shows in Canada in late June 2009 with openers<space/><link><target>Machine Head (band)</target><part>Machine Head</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Suicide Silence</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=118898</param>\n<param name="title">MEGADETH And SLAYER To Co-Headline 'Canadian Carnage' Trek</param>\n<param name="publisher">Roadrunnerrecords.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="accessdate">2010-11-07</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.Net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=118898</param>\n<param name="title">MEGADETH And SLAYER To Co-Headline 'Canadian Carnage' Trek</param>\n<param name="publisher">Roadrunnerrecords.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="accessdate">2010-11-07</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/151">This was followed by further dates in Canada and also in the US during the Summer and <link synthetic="true"><target>Shadows Fall</target><part>Fall</part></link> of 2010 with openers<space/><link><target>Testament (band)</target><part>Testament</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Anthrax (band)</target><part>Anthrax</part></link>.</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/152">The band's tenth studio album<space/><italics><link><target>World Painted Blood</target></link></italics><space/>has been released on <link synthetic="true"><target>American Recordings (US)</target><part>American Recordings</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/153">It was available on November 3 in North America and November 2 for the rest of the world.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/154">The band has stated that the<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>World Painted Blood</target><part>Painted Blood</part></link></italics><space/>takes parts of all their previous works including<space/><italics>Seasons...</italics>,<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>South of Heaven</target></link></italics>, and<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref">Carman, Keith<space/><link type="external" href="http://exclaim.ca/articles/multiarticlesub.aspx?csid1=138&amp;amp;csid2=9&amp;amp;fid1=42058">Slayer Reign Supreme</link><space/>at<space/><italics><link><target>Exclaim!</target></link></italics><space/>December 2009.</extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/155"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>, along with <link synthetic="true"><target>Metallica</target></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Megadeth</target></link>, and <link synthetic="true"><target>Anthrax (band)</target><part>Anthrax</part></link> performed on the same bill for the first time on June 16, 2010 at Bemowo Airport (<link><target>Warsaw</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Poland</target></link>).</sentence> <sentence id="73575/156">It was the first performance of that bands played as a part of Sonisphere <link synthetic="true"><target>Download festival</target><part>Festival</part></link> series, one of the following (<link><target>Sofia</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Bulgaria</target></link>, June 22, 2010) was sent via satellite in HD to cinemas.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Metallica</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/news/metallica-heading-to-cinemas-1004097367.story#/news/metallica-heading-to-cinemas-1004097367.story</param>\n<param name="title">Metallica Heading To Cinemas</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="date">2009-09-14</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2010-11-07</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Metallica</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/news/metallica-heading-to-cinemas-1004097367.story#/news/metallica-heading-to-cinemas-1004097367.story</param>\n<param name="title">Metallica Heading To Cinemas</param>\n<param name="publisher">Billboard.com</param>\n<param name="date">2009-09-14</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2010-11-07</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/157">They also went on to play in<space/><link><target>Switzerland</target></link><space/>(June 18, 2010),<space/><link><target>Milovice</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Czech Republic</target></link><space/>(June 19, 2010),<space/><link><target>Bucharest</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Romania</target></link><space/>(June 26, 2010) and then in<space/><link><target>Istanbul</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Turkey</target></link><space/>(June 27, 2010) also as part of the Sonisphere <link synthetic="true"><target>Download festival</target><part>Festival</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/158">On December 18, 2010, it was announced that<space/><link><target>Megadeth</target></link><space/>and <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> will join forces once again for European Carnage Tour in March and <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=151107</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER, MEGADETH To Join Forces For 'European Carnage' Tour</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=151107</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER, MEGADETH To Join Forces For 'European Carnage' Tour</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/159">Also the "<link synthetic="true"><target>Big 4</target><part>Big</part></link> Four" will play couple of dates again at Sonisphere in England and France for the first time ever.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.soundwavetouring.com/</param>\n<param name="title">Soundwave Touring</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.soundwavetouring.com/</param>\n<param name="title">Soundwave Touring</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/160"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> will be returning to Australia in February and March 2011 as part of the<space/><link><target>Soundwave (Australian music festival)</target><part>Soundwave Festival</part></link><space/>and will also play in <link synthetic="true"><target>Southern California</target><part>California</part></link> with the other members of the "<link synthetic="true"><target>Big 4</target><part>Big</part></link> Four".</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/161">In early 2011, <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> contracted<space/><link><target>necrotizing fasciitis</target></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/162">According to the band, doctors say that it likely originated from a spider bite.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/163">In light of this situation and <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> participation in the Australian <link synthetic="true"><target>Soundwave (Australian music festival)</target><part>Soundwave Festival</part></link> tour set to kick off on February 26, the band made the tough decision to play the dates without <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=153855</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER's HANNEMAN Contracts Acute Infection; Band To Bring In Guest Guitarist</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=153855</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER's HANNEMAN Contracts Acute Infection; Band To Bring In Guest Guitarist</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/164"><link><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Gary Holt</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link><space/>has been announced as <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Jeff's</part></link> temporary replacement.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="blab-garyholt"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=154012</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Recruits EXODUS Guitarist GARY HOLT For Upcoming Tour - Feb. 15, 2011</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=154012</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Recruits EXODUS Guitarist GARY HOLT For Upcoming Tour - Feb. 15, 2011</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/165"><link synthetic="true"><target>Thrash metal</target><part>Metal</part></link> website <link synthetic="true"><target>Thrash metal</target><part>Metal</part></link> Underground used this to their advantage when they posted a joke article on<space/><link><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April 1</part></link>, 2011 that suggested <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> had actually left the band.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=66813</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer Guitarist Jeff Hanneman Leaves the Band - Apr. 1, 2011</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=66813</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer Guitarist Jeff Hanneman Leaves the Band - Apr. 1, 2011</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/166">The article was picked up and distributed by other sites and social media, leading to initial dismay from fans.</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/167"><link><target>Cannibal Corpse</target></link><space/>guitarist<space/><link><target>Pat O'Brien (guitarist)</target><part>Pat O'Brien</part></link><space/>will fill in for<space/><link><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link>'<space/><link><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Gary Holt</part></link><space/>when <link synthetic="true"><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Holt</part></link> leaves the <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> European tour to play with his own band <link synthetic="true"><target>Exodus (band)</target><part>Exodus</part></link> at the Estadio Nacional in Santiago,<space/><link><target>Chile</target></link><space/>on <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> 10.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/168"><link synthetic="true"><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Holt's</part></link> last show with <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> will be <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> 4 in<space/><link><target>Padova</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Italy</target></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Pat O'Brien (guitarist)</target><part>O'Brien</part></link> will join the band for the <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> 6 show in<space/><link><target>Croatia</target></link>, and will finish the European dates with <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> that wrap up on <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> 14 in<space/><link><target>Holland</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="slayer1"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.slayer.net/us/news/cannibal-corpses-pat-obrien-will-step-slayers-guest-guitarist</param>\n<param name="title">Cannibal Corpse'S Pat O'Brien Will Step In As Slayer'S Guest Guitarist &amp;#124; The Official Slayer Site</param>\n<param name="publisher">Slayer.net</param>\n<param name="date">2011-05-19</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2011-07-01</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.slayer.net/us/news/cannibal-corpses-pat-obrien-will-step-slayers-guest-guitarist</param>\n<param name="title">Cannibal Corpse'S Pat O'Brien Will Step In As Slayer'S Guest Guitarist &amp;#124; The Official Slayer Site</param>\n<param name="publisher">Slayer.net</param>\n<param name="date">2011-05-19</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2011-07-01</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/169"><link><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Gary Holt</part></link><space/>rejoined <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> on <link synthetic="true"><target>April Fool's Day</target><part>April</part></link> 23, 2011, at the<space/><link><target>Big 4</target></link><space/>show, in the<space/><link><target>United States</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Josh Hart</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.revolvermag.com/news/update-gary-holt-will-join-slayer-for-big-four-show.html</param>\n<param name="title">Update: Gary Holt Will Join Slayer For Big Four Show - Revolver Magazine</param>\n<param name="publisher">Revolvermag.com</param>\n<param name="date">2011-04-21</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2011-07-01</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Josh Hart</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.revolvermag.com/news/update-gary-holt-will-join-slayer-for-big-four-show.html</param>\n<param name="title">Update: Gary Holt Will Join Slayer For Big Four Show - Revolver Magazine</param>\n<param name="publisher">Revolvermag.com</param>\n<param name="date">2011-04-21</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2011-07-01</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/170"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link> replaced <link synthetic="true"><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Holt</part></link> during the final two songs, "<link synthetic="true"><target>South of Heaven</target></link>" and "<link synthetic="true"><target>Angel of Death (song)</target><part>Angel of Death</part></link>".</sentence></paragraph><heading level="3">Next album</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/171">In a May 2011 interview with Geeks of Doom, drummer<space/><link><target>Dave Lombardo</target></link><space/>was asked if <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> was going to make another album.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/172">He replied, "Yes absolutely.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/173">Although there's nothing written but there is definitely plans.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/174">Of course.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/175">We have to!</sentence> <sentence id="73575/176">Why not?! [laughs] I'm not retiring and I don't think <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>Kerry's</part></link> retiring either so..</sentence>.<space/><sentence id="73575/177"><link><target>Charlie Watts</target></link><space/>is somebody I look up to and for someone to be on those drums for as long as he's been up there then I'm on my way!</sentence> <sentence id="73575/178">I'm right behind him, man! [laughs] I'm one of those guys.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/179">I like longevity and a true musician never abandons his art.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=158701</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Drummer Says He 'Wasn't A Fan' Of Band's Albums He Didn't Play On</param>\n<param name="publisher">BlabberMouth</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=158701</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Drummer Says He 'Wasn't A Fan' Of Band's Albums He Didn't Play On</param>\n<param name="publisher">BlabberMouth</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/180">However, according to bassist/vocalist<space/><link><target>Tom Araya</target></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> will not begin writing a new album until<space/><link><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link>'s condition improves.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="last">Graff</param>\n<param name="first">Gary</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer to 'Hold Off' on Recording While Ailing Bassist Recovers</param>\n<param name="work"><link><target>Billboard (magazine)</target><part>Billboard</part></link></param>\n<param name="date">May 31, 2011</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/news/slayer-to-hold-off-on-recording-while-ailing-1005206572.story#/news/slayer-to-hold-off-on-recording-while-ailing-1005206572.story</param>\n<param name="accessdate">May 31, 2011</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="last">Graff</param>\n<param name="first">Gary</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer to 'Hold Off' on Recording While Ailing Bassist Recovers</param>\n<param name="work"><link><target>Billboard (magazine)</target><part>Billboard</part></link></param>\n<param name="date">May 31, 2011</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.billboard.com/news/slayer-to-hold-off-on-recording-while-ailing-1005206572.story#/news/slayer-to-hold-off-on-recording-while-ailing-1005206572.story</param>\n<param name="accessdate">May 31, 2011</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="2">Writing and style</heading><paragraph><link><target>Image:SlayerliveB&amp;W.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>240px</part><part>Hanneman, Araya and King are the main contributors for the band's lyrics</part></link><sentence id="73575/181">Early works were praised for their "breakneck speed and instrumental prowess", combining the structure of<space/><link><target>hardcore punk</target><part>hardcore</part></link><space/>tempos and<space/><link><target>speed metal</target></link><space/>the band released fast, aggressive material.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Allmusic Biography of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/182">The album<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics><space/>is the band's fastest, performed at an average of 220<space/><link><target>beats per minute</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Andrew Haug speaks with Dave Lombardo from Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Andrew Haug speaks with Dave Lombardo from Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Haug, Andrew</param>\n<param name="work">Racket</param>\n<param name="publisher">Triple J</param>\n<param name="date">13 October 2006</param>\n<param name="format">MP3</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/racket/interviews/fmr_slayer.mp3</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 June 2010</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Andrew Haug speaks with Dave Lombardo from Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Haug, Andrew</param>\n<param name="work">Racket</param>\n<param name="publisher">Triple J</param>\n<param name="date">13 October 2006</param>\n<param name="format">MP3</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/racket/interviews/fmr_slayer.mp3</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 June 2010</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/183">The album<space/><italics><link><target>Diabolus in Musica</target></link></italics><space/>was the band's first with<space/><link><target>drop D tuning</target></link>,<space/><italics><link><target>God Hates Us All</target></link></italics><space/>the first with C# tuning.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="SlayerBIOGRAPHY"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Biography</param>\n<param name="publisher">hardcoresounds.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.hardcoresounds.net/modules.php?name=Band_List&amp;file=viewer&amp;func=356</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Biography</param>\n<param name="publisher">hardcoresounds.net</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.hardcoresounds.net/modules.php?name=Band_List&amp;file=viewer&amp;func=356</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/184"><italics><link><target>Allmusic</target></link></italics><space/>cited the album as "abandoning the extravagances and accessibility of their late-'80s/early-'90s work and returning to perfect the raw approach",<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer - God Hates us all"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - God Hates us all</param>\n<param name="author">Birchmeier, Jason</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Allmusic</target></link></param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r541496</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - God Hates us all</param>\n<param name="author">Birchmeier, Jason</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Allmusic</target></link></param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r541496</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>with some fans labeling it<space/><link><target>nu metal</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name=" Paul Bostaph of Exodus, ex-Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Paul Bostaph of Exodus, ex-Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Syrjälä, Marko</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-Rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">5 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&amp;task=view&amp;id=797&amp;Itemid=60</param>\n<param name="accessdate">7 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Paul Bostaph of Exodus, ex-Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Syrjälä, Marko</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-Rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">5 February 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/zine/index.php?option=content&amp;task=view&amp;id=797&amp;Itemid=60</param>\n<param name="accessdate">7 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/185"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link>’s dual<space/><link><target>guitar solos</target></link><space/>have been called "wildly chaotic",<extension extension_name="ref" name="Allmusic Biography of Slayer"/><space/>and "twisted genius".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer - Reign in Blood"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Reign in Blood</param>\n<param name="author">Horatio</param>\n<param name="publisher">Kickedintheface.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kickedintheface.com/reviews/Slayer-Reign_In_Blood.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer - Reign in Blood</param>\n<param name="author">Horatio</param>\n<param name="publisher">Kickedintheface.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.kickedintheface.com/reviews/Slayer-Reign_In_Blood.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/186">Drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> uses two bass drums, instead of the<space/><link><target>Double bass drum</target><part>double kick</part></link><space/>which is used on a single bass drum.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/187"><link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo's</part></link> speed and aggression earned him the title of the “godfather of double bass” by <link synthetic="true"><target>Drummerworld</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Drummerworld - Dave Lombardo"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Drummerworld - Dave Lombardo</param>\n<param name="publisher">Drummerworld.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Dave_Lombardo.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">30 January 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Drummerworld - Dave Lombardo</param>\n<param name="publisher">Drummerworld.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Dave_Lombardo.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">30 January 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/188"><link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> states his reasons for using two bass drums: "When you hit the bass drum the head is still resonating.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/189">When you hit it in the same place right after that you kinda get a 'slapback' from the bass drum head hitting the other pedal.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/190">You're not letting them breathe."</sentence> <sentence id="73575/191">When playing the double bass <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> uses the<space/><link><target>Bass drum#Techniques</target><part>"heel-up" technique</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref">Dave Lombardo Modern Drummer Festival 2000</extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/192"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> contribute to the band's lyrics, and <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> create the music, with no assistance from <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> or <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link>.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/193">In fact <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> has not received any writing credits in <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> history.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/194"><link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> has formed a lyric writing partnership with <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link>, which can overshadow the creative input of <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="An exclusive oral history of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/195"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> states writing lyrics and music is a "free for all"; "It’s all just whoever comes up with what.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/196">Sometimes I’ll be more on a roll and I’ll have more stuff, same with <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>Kerry</part></link>—it’s whoever's hot, really.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/197">Anybody can write anything; if it’s good we use it, if not we don’t.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="autogenerated3"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Davis, Brian</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3153</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Davis, Brian</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=3153</param>\n<param name="accessdate">13 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/198">When writing new material, the band writes the music before incorporating lyrics.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/199"><link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> or <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> will use a<space/><link><target>Multitrack recording</target><part>24-track</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>drum machine</target></link><space/>to show band members the riff they have created, and to get their opinion.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/200">Either <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> or <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> will mention if any alterations can be made.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/201">The band will play the riff to get the basic song structure, and figure out where the lyrics and solos will be placed.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Knac.com interview with Jeff Hanneman"/><space/><sentence id="73575/202"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link>, <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> tend to have different lyrical influences.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/203"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman's</part></link> lyrics deal with <link synthetic="true"><target>Nazism</target><part>Nazis</part></link>, religion, warfare and similar topics.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/204"><link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King's</part></link> lyrics are generally just very anti-religious.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/205"><link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya's</part></link> lyrics usually deal with less controversial topics than <link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> such as serial killers and warfare.</sentence></paragraph><heading level="2">Awards and nominations</heading><heading level="3">Grammy Awards</heading><paragraph><template name="awards table">\n</template>|-| style="text-align:center;"| 2002 || <sentence id="73575/206">"Disciple" || <link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link> ||<space/><template name="nom">\n</template>|-| style="text-align:center;"| 2007 || "<link synthetic="true"><target>Eyes of the Insane</target></link>" || <link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link> ||<space/><template name="won">\n</template>|-| style="text-align:center;"| 2008 || "Final Six" || <link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link> ||<space/><template name="won">\n</template>|-| style="text-align:center;"| 2010 || "Hate Worldwide" || <link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link> ||<space/><template name="nom">\n</template>|-| style="text-align:center;"| 2011 || "<link synthetic="true"><target>World Painted Blood</target></link>" || <link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target></link> ||<space/><template name="nom">\n</template>|-<template name="end">\n</template></sentence></paragraph><heading level="2">Legacy</heading><paragraph><link><target>Image:DaveLombardo.png</target><part>thumb</part><part>left</part><part>200px</part><part>Lombardo's speed and aggression earned him the title of the “godfather of double bass” by ''<link><target>Drummerworld</target></link>''.</part></link><sentence id="73575/207"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> are one of the most influential <link synthetic="true"><target>American Recordings (US)</target><part>American</part></link> heavy metal bands.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/208">Steve Huey of<space/><link><target>Allmusic</target></link><space/>believes the musical style of <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> makes the band stronger than the other members of the "<link synthetic="true"><target>Big 4</target><part>Big</part></link> Four" thrash metal bands<space/><link><target>Metallica</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Megadeth</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Anthrax (band)</target><part>Anthrax</part></link>, all of which rose to fame during the 1980s.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Allmusic Biography of Slayer"/><space/><sentence id="73575/209"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> "downtuned rhythms, infectious guitar licks, graphically violent lyrics and grisly artwork set the standard for dozens of emerging thrash bands" and their "music was directly responsible for the rise of death metal" states<space/><link><target>MTV</target></link>, ranking <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> as the sixth "greatest metal band of all time",<extension extension_name="ref" name="Why They Rule - #6 Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Why They Rule - #6 Slayer</param>\n<param name="publisher">MTV</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.mtv.com/bands/m/metal/greatest_metal_bands/071406/index7.jhtml</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Why They Rule - #6 Slayer</param>\n<param name="publisher">MTV</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.mtv.com/bands/m/metal/greatest_metal_bands/071406/index7.jhtml</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>also ranking number 50 on<space/><link><target>VH1</target></link>'s<space/><italics>100 Greatest Artists of Hard <link synthetic="true"><target>Fields of Rock</target><part>Rock</part></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="The Greatest: 100 Greatest Artists of Hard Rock"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The Greatest: 100 Greatest Artists of Hard Rock</param>\n<param name="publisher">VH1.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/62186/episode_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=/shows/dynamic/includes/wildcards/the_greatest/hardrock_list_full.jhtml&amp;event_id=862767&amp;start=41</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The Greatest: 100 Greatest Artists of Hard Rock</param>\n<param name="publisher">VH1.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/62186/episode_wildcard.jhtml?wildcard=/shows/dynamic/includes/wildcards/the_greatest/hardrock_list_full.jhtml&amp;event_id=862767&amp;start=41</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/210"><link synthetic="true"><target>Jeff Hanneman</target><part>Hanneman</part></link> and <link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> ranked number 10 in<space/><link><target>Guitar World</target></link>'s "100 greatest metal guitarists of all time" in 2004,<extension extension_name="ref" name="GUITAR WORLD's 100 Greatest Heavy Metal Guitarists Of All Time"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Guitar World's 100 Greatest Heavy Metal Guitarists Of All Time</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">23 January 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=18446</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Guitar World's 100 Greatest Heavy Metal Guitarists Of All Time</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">23 January 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=18446</param>\n<param name="accessdate">18 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and were voted "<link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target><part>Best</part></link> Guitarist/<link synthetic="true"><target>guitar solos</target><part>Guitar</part></link> Team" in<space/><link><target>Revolver (magazine)</target><part>Revolver's</part></link><space/>reader's poll.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/211"><link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> was also voted "<link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target><part>Best</part></link> Drummer" and the band entered the top five in the categories "<link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target><part>Best</part></link> Band Ever", "<link synthetic="true"><target>Best Metal Performance</target><part>Best</part></link> <link synthetic="true"><target>live album</target><part>Live</part></link> Band", "<link synthetic="true"><target>Show No Mercy</target><part>Album</part></link> of the Year" (for<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Christ Illusion</target></link></italics>), and "Band of the Year".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="The fans have spoken: Slayer comes out on top in readers' polls"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The fans have spoken: Slayer comes out on top in readers' polls</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">1 March 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=68001</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 March 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">The fans have spoken: Slayer comes out on top in readers' polls</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">1 March 2007</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=68001</param>\n<param name="accessdate">16 March 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/212">The band's 1986 release<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics><space/>has been an influence to extreme and thrash metal bands since its release.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/213">The album was hailed the "heaviest album of all time" by<space/><italics><link><target>Kerrang!</target></link><space/><link synthetic="true"><target>Stylus Magazine</target><part>Magazine</part></link></italics>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Kerrang! Hall Of Fame"/><space/>a "genre-definer" by<space/><italics><link><target>Stylus Magazine</target></link></italics>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Jarvis, Clay</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Stylus Magazine</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">1 September 2003</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/slayer/reign-in-blood.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer</param>\n<param name="author">Jarvis, Clay</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Stylus Magazine</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">1 September 2003</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.stylusmagazine.com/reviews/slayer/reign-in-blood.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">19 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and a "stone-cold classic upon its release" by<space/><italics><link><target>Allmusic</target></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Reign in Blood"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Reign in Blood</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18220</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Reign in Blood</param>\n<param name="author">Huey, Steve</param>\n<param name="publisher">Allmusic</param>\n<param name="url"><template name="Allmusic">\n<param name="class">album</param>\n<param name="id">r18220</param>\n<param name="pure_url">yes</param>\n</template></param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/214">In 2006 it was named the best metal album of the last 20 years by<space/><italics><link><target>Metal Hammer</target></link></italics>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Golden Gods Awards Winners"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Golden Gods Awards Winners</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Metal Hammer</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">13 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/?id=44410</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Golden Gods Awards Winners</param>\n<param name="publisher"><link><target>Metal Hammer</target></link></param>\n<param name="date">13 June 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/?id=44410</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 January 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/215"><link><target>Richard Christy</target></link>, former member of<space/><link><target>Death (metal band)</target><part>Death</part></link><space/>was blown away by <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Dave's</part></link> performance on the album<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Reign in Blood</target></link></italics>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="A Conversation With Richard Christy"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">A Conversation With Richard Christy</param>\n<param name="author">Bowar, Chad</param>\n<param name="publisher">about.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://heavymetal.about.com/od/interviews/a/richardchristy_3.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">A Conversation With Richard Christy</param>\n<param name="author">Bowar, Chad</param>\n<param name="publisher">about.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://heavymetal.about.com/od/interviews/a/richardchristy_3.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>as was<space/><link><target>Cannibal Corpse</target></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Paul Mazurkiewicz</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Interview With Paul Mazurkiewicz of Cannibal Corpse"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview With Paul Mazurkiewicz of Cannibal Corpse</param>\n<param name="author">L. Wilson, David</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-Rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">13 December 1998</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/interviews/cannibal.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview With Paul Mazurkiewicz of Cannibal Corpse</param>\n<param name="author">L. Wilson, David</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metal-Rules.com</param>\n<param name="date">13 December 1998</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metal-rules.com/interviews/cannibal.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/216">Drummer <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link> has been an influence on many modern metal drummers including<space/><link><target>Raymond Herrera</target><part>Ray Herrera</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Fear Factory</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Fear Factory screams through the U.S. on Machines At War Tour"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Fear Factory screams through the U.S. on Machines At War Tour</param>\n<param name="author">Wolf, DC</param>\n<param name="publisher">Tuftsdaily.com</param>\n<param name="date">16 November 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2006/11/16/Weekender/Weekender.Interview.Fear.Factory-2463687.shtml</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Fear Factory screams through the U.S. on Machines At War Tour</param>\n<param name="author">Wolf, DC</param>\n<param name="publisher">Tuftsdaily.com</param>\n<param name="date">16 November 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2006/11/16/Weekender/Weekender.Interview.Fear.Factory-2463687.shtml</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><link><target>Pete Sandoval</target></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Morbid Angel</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="MORBID ANGEL interview"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Morbid Angel interview</param>\n<param name="author">Cortez, Rick</param>\n<param name="publisher">Voicesfromthedarkside.de</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Morbid Angel interview</param>\n<param name="author">Cortez, Rick</param>\n<param name="publisher">Voicesfromthedarkside.de</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.voicesfromthedarkside.de/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>former<space/><link><target>Cradle of Filth</target></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Adrian Erlandsson</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name=" INTERVIEW WITH ADRIAN ERLANDSSON"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with ADrian Erlandsson</param>\n<param name="author">Tobin, Dan</param>\n<param name="publisher">Earache.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.earache.com/WickedWorld/interview/cradle_of_filth/cradle_of_filth.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with ADrian Erlandsson</param>\n<param name="author">Tobin, Dan</param>\n<param name="publisher">Earache.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.earache.com/WickedWorld/interview/cradle_of_filth/cradle_of_filth.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>and<space/><link><target>Krisiun</target></link><space/>drummer<space/><link><target>Max Kolesne</target></link>.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Krisiun"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Krisiun</param>\n<param name="author">German, Eric</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalupdate.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalupdate.com/interviewkrisiun.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Krisiun</param>\n<param name="author">German, Eric</param>\n<param name="publisher">Metalupdate.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.metalupdate.com/interviewkrisiun.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/217">Patrick Grün of<space/><link><target>Caliban (band)</target><part>Caliban's</part></link><space/>inspiration to play drums came from <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo</part></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="Caliban - Living The Dream"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Caliban - Living The Dream</param>\n<param name="author">Day, Tom</param>\n<param name="publisher">MusicOHM.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.musicomh.com/interviews/caliban.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Caliban - Living The Dream</param>\n<param name="author">Day, Tom</param>\n<param name="publisher">MusicOHM.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.musicomh.com/interviews/caliban.htm</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/>with<space/><link><target>Jason Bittner</target></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>Shadows Fall</target></link><space/>inspired by <link synthetic="true"><target>Dave Lombardo</target><part>Lombardo's</part></link> double bass, utilizing double bass when starting his own music career.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name=" Proving Speed, Power, And Musicality Can Go Hand In Hand"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Proving Speed, Power, And Musicality Can Go Hand In Hand</param>\n<param name="author">Haid, Mark</param>\n<param name="publisher">Moderndrummer.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.moderndrummer.com/updatefull/200001128</param>\n<param name="accessdate">23 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Proving Speed, Power, And Musicality Can Go Hand In Hand</param>\n<param name="author">Haid, Mark</param>\n<param name="publisher">Moderndrummer.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.moderndrummer.com/updatefull/200001128</param>\n<param name="accessdate">23 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><heading level="2">Controversy</heading><paragraph><sentence id="73575/218"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> has been accused of holding<space/><link><target>Nazism</target><part>Nazi</part></link><space/>sympathies, due to the band's eagle logo bearing resemblance to the<space/><link><target>Eagle atop swastika</target></link><space/>and the lyrics of "<link><target>Angel of Death (song)</target><part>Angel of Death</part></link>".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Kerry King: Maniac. Guitar Legend. Botanist?"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerry King: Maniac. Guitar Legend. Botanist?</param>\n<param name="author">Hess, Mike</param>\n<param name="publisher">Nighttimes.com</param>\n<param name="date">23 July 2003</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.nighttimes.com/nt_main.asp?aID=388</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Kerry King: Maniac. Guitar Legend. Botanist?</param>\n<param name="author">Hess, Mike</param>\n<param name="publisher">Nighttimes.com</param>\n<param name="date">23 July 2003</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.nighttimes.com/nt_main.asp?aID=388</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/219"><link synthetic="true"><target>Angel of Death (song)</target><part>Angel of Death</part></link> was inspired by the acts of<space/><link><target>Josef Mengele</target></link>,<extension extension_name="ref" name="autogenerated1"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with Slayer Guitarist Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Steffens, Charlie</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="date">30 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=4653</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Interview with Slayer Guitarist Jeff Hanneman</param>\n<param name="author">Steffens, Charlie</param>\n<param name="publisher">Knac.com</param>\n<param name="date">30 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=4653</param>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/>the doctor who conducted<space/><link><target>human experiments</target></link><space/>on prisoners during<space/><link><target>World War II</target></link><space/>at the<space/><link><target>Auschwitz concentration camp</target></link>, and was dubbed the "<link synthetic="true"><target>Angel of Death (song)</target><part>Angel of Death</part></link>" by inmates.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="moreorless : heroes &amp;amp; killers of the 20th century - Josef Mengele"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">moreorless : heroes &amp;amp; killers of the 20th century - Josef Mengele</param>\n<param name="publisher">Moreorless.com</param>\n<param name="date">30 April 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.moreorless.au.com/killers/mengele.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">moreorless : heroes &amp;amp; killers of the 20th century - Josef Mengele</param>\n<param name="publisher">Moreorless.com</param>\n<param name="date">30 April 2001</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.moreorless.au.com/killers/mengele.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">1 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/220">Throughout their career, the band members were asked about these accusations, and have stated numerous times they do not condone <link synthetic="true"><target>Nazism</target></link> and are merely interested in the subject.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer’s Tom Araya on Satanism, serial killers and his lovable kids"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayers Tom Araya on Satanism, serial killers and his lovable kids</param>\n<param name="author">Cummins, Johnson</param>\n<param name="publisher">MontrealMirror.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2002/012402/music1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayers Tom Araya on Satanism, serial killers and his lovable kids</param>\n<param name="author">Cummins, Johnson</param>\n<param name="publisher">MontrealMirror.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2002/012402/music1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/221"><link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> cover of<space/><link><target>Minor Threat</target><part>Minor Threat's</part></link><space/>"Guilty of Being <link synthetic="true"><target>white supremacy</target><part>White</part></link>" raised questions about a possible message of<space/><link><target>white supremacy</target></link><space/>in the band's music.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/222">The controversy surrounding the cover involved the changing of the refrain "guilty of being white" to "guilty of being right", at the song's ending.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/223">This incensed <link synthetic="true"><target>Minor Threat</target></link> frontman<space/><link><target>Ian MacKaye</target></link>, who stated "that is so offensive to me.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref">Blush, Steven<space/><italics>American Hardcore: A Tribal History by Steven Blush</italics><space/>(New York: Feral House, 2001), "Guilty of Being White," in an interview with Ian MacKaye, 30–31.</extension><space/><sentence id="73575/224"><link synthetic="true"><target>Kerry King</target><part>King</part></link> said it was changed for "tongue-in-cheek" humor as he thought the allegation of racism at the time was "ridiculous".</sentence><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Alpha69 Productions, Perceptive Minds, SERANO</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.toazted.com/interview/100/Slayer.html</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer interviews (audio, mp3, video)</param>\n<param name="publisher">Toazted.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2008</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="author">Alpha69 Productions, Perceptive Minds, SERANO</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.toazted.com/interview/100/Slayer.html</param>\n<param name="title">Slayer interviews (audio, mp3, video)</param>\n<param name="publisher">Toazted.com</param>\n<param name="date"/>\n<param name="accessdate">10 December 2008</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/225">In a 2004 interview with <link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link>, when asked, "Did critics realize you were wallowing in parody?"</sentence>, <sentence id="73575/226"><link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> replied, "No.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/227">People thought we were serious!...back then you had that<space/><link><target>Parents Music Resource Center</target><part>PMRC</part></link>, who literally took everything to heart, when in actuality you're trying to create an image.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/228">You're trying to scare people on purpose.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="Westword interview with Tom Araya"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Westword interview with Tom Araya</param>\n<param name="author">La Briola, John</param>\n<param name="publisher">Westword.com</param>\n<param name="date">22 July 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.westword.com/2004-07-22/music/slay-ride/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">7 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Westword interview with Tom Araya</param>\n<param name="author">La Briola, John</param>\n<param name="publisher">Westword.com</param>\n<param name="date">22 July 2004</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.westword.com/2004-07-22/music/slay-ride/</param>\n<param name="accessdate">7 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/229"><link synthetic="true"><target>Tom Araya</target><part>Araya</part></link> also denied rumors that <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link> members are<space/><link><target>Satanists</target></link>, but they find the subject of <link synthetic="true"><target>Satanism</target></link> interesting and "we are all on this planet to learn and experience.</sentence>"<extension extension_name="ref" name="autogenerated2"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayers Tom Araya on Satanism, serial killers and his lovable kids</param>\n<param name="author">Cummins, Johnson</param>\n<param name="publisher">MontrealMirror.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2002/012402/music1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayers Tom Araya on Satanism, serial killers and his lovable kids</param>\n<param name="author">Cummins, Johnson</param>\n<param name="publisher">MontrealMirror.com</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2002/012402/music1.html</param>\n<param name="accessdate">2 December 2006</param>\n</template></extension><sentence id="73575/230"><link><target>File:Slayer at The Fields of Rock festival.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part>270px</part><part>Due to its controversial artwork, all Indian stocks of ''<link><target>Christ Illusion</target></link>'' ''(pictured in background)'' were recalled and destroyed</part></link></sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/231">The song "<link><target>Jihad (song)</target><part>Jihad</part></link>" of the album<space/><italics><link synthetic="true"><target>Christ Illusion</target></link></italics><space/>sparked controversy among families of the <link synthetic="true"><target>September 11, 2001</target><part>September 11</part></link> victims.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer SPARK 9/11 CONTROVERSY"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer spark 9/11 Controversy</param>\n<param name="publisher">Contactmusic.com</param>\n<param name="date">26 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/slayer%20spark%20911%20controversy_26_05_2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer spark 9/11 Controversy</param>\n<param name="publisher">Contactmusic.com</param>\n<param name="date">26 May 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/slayer%20spark%20911%20controversy_26_05_2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">29 November 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/232">The song deals with the attack from the perspective of a religious terrorist.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/233">The band stated the song is spoken through perspective without being sympathetic to the cause, and supports neither side.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer SPARK 9/11 CONTROVERSY"/><space/></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/234">Seventeen bus benches promoting the album in<space/><link><target>Fullerton, California</target></link><space/>were deemed offensive by city officials.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/235">They felt the Antichrist and skull were inappropriate, and felt the name "<link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target></link>" pertains to a murderer.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/236">City officials contacted the band's record label and demanded that the ads be removed.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Exclusive: City Of Fullerton Demands That Slayer Bus Benches Be Removed "><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Exclusive: City Of Fullerton demands that Slayer bus benches be removed</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">1 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=55902</param>\n<param name="accessdate">17 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Exclusive: City Of Fullerton demands that Slayer bus benches be removed</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">1 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=55902</param>\n<param name="accessdate">17 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/237">All seventeen benches were removed.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="Slayer 'Christ Illusion' Bus Benches Removed From Fullerton"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer 'Christ Illusion' bus benches removed from Fullerton</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">8 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=56141</param>\n<param name="accessdate">17 January 2006</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer 'Christ Illusion' bus benches removed from Fullerton</param>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">8 August 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=56141</param>\n<param name="accessdate">17 January 2006</param>\n</template></extension></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/238">In India, the album was recalled by<space/><link><target>EMI</target></link><space/>India after protests with<space/><link><target>Christian</target></link><space/>religious groups due to the nature of the graphic artwork.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/239">The album cover was designed by <link synthetic="true"><target>Slayer</target><part>Slayer's</part></link> longtime collaborator<space/><link><target>Larry Carroll (artist)</target><part>Larry Carroll</part></link><space/>and features <link synthetic="true"><target>Christ Illusion</target><part>Christ</part></link> in a "sea of despair", while having amputated arms, missing an eye, while standing in a sea of blood with severed heads.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="EMI"><template name="cite news">\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6039976.stm</param>\n<param name="title">India bans 'offensive' rock album</param>\n<param name="date">11 October 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">11 October 2006</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n</template><template name="cite news">\n<param name="url">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6039976.stm</param>\n<param name="title">India bans 'offensive' rock album</param>\n<param name="date">11 October 2006</param>\n<param name="accessdate">11 October 2006</param>\n<param name="publisher">BBC News</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/240">Joseph Dias of the Mumbai <link synthetic="true"><target>Christian</target></link> group<space/><italics>Catholic Secular Forum</italics><space/>in India took "strong exception" to the original album artwork, and issued a memorandum to Mumbai's police commissioner in protest.</sentence> <sentence id="73575/241">Although since 2011, <link synthetic="true"><target>Sony Music Entertainment</target><part>Sony music</part></link> has started selling imported stock of the album in India.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="IllusionRecalled"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's 'Christ Illusion' Album Recalled Following Christian Group Protests</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">6 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=59883</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="title">Slayer's 'Christ Illusion' Album Recalled Following Christian Group Protests</param>\n<param name="author"/>\n<param name="publisher">Blabbermouth.net</param>\n<param name="date">6 October 2006</param>\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=59883</param>\n<param name="accessdate">22 February 2007</param>\n</template></extension><space/><sentence id="73575/242">On October 11, 2006, <link synthetic="true"><target>EMI</target></link> announced that all stocks had been destroyed, noting it had no plans to re-release the record in India in the future.</sentence><extension extension_name="ref" name="EMI"/></paragraph><heading level="2">Band members</heading><list type="def"><listitem><defkey>Current</defkey></listitem></list><list type="bullet"><listitem><sentence id="73575/243"><link><target>Tom Araya</target></link><space/>–<space/><link><target>Lead vocalist</target><part>lead vocals</part></link>,<space/><link><target>bass guitar</target><part>bass</part></link><space/>(1981–present)</sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/244"><link><target>Jeff Hanneman</target></link><space/>–<space/><link><target>electric guitar</target><part>guitars</part></link><space/>(1981–present)</sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/245"><link><target>Kerry King</target></link><space/>– guitars (1981–present)</sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/246"><link><target>Dave Lombardo</target></link><space/>–<space/><link><target>drum kit</target><part>drums</part></link><space/>(1981–1986, 1987–1992, 2001–present)</sentence></listitem></list><list type="def"><listitem><defkey>Touring</defkey></listitem></list><list type="bullet"><listitem><sentence id="73575/247"><link><target>Gary Holt (musician)</target><part>Gary Holt</part></link><space/>-<space/><link><target>guitars</target></link><space/>(2011)<space/><extension extension_name="ref"><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=154012</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Recruits EXODUS Guitarist GARY HOLT For Upcoming Tour</param>\n<param name="publisher">BlabberMouth</param>\n</template><template name="cite web">\n<param name="url">http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&amp;newsitemID=154012</param>\n<param name="title">SLAYER Recruits EXODUS Guitarist GARY HOLT For Upcoming Tour</param>\n<param name="publisher">BlabberMouth</param>\n</template></extension></sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/248"><link><target>Pat O'Brien (guitarist)</target><part>Pat O'Brien</part></link><space/>-<space/><link><target>guitars</target></link><space/>(2011)<space/><extension extension_name="ref" name="slayer1"/></sentence></listitem></list><list type="def"><listitem><defkey>Former</defkey></listitem></list><list type="bullet"><listitem><sentence id="73575/249"><link><target>Tony Scaglione</target></link><space/>–<space/><link><target>drum kit</target><part>drums</part></link><space/>(1986–1987)</sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/250"><link><target>Paul Bostaph</target></link><space/>– drums (1992–1996, 1997–2001)</sentence></listitem><listitem><sentence id="73575/251"><link><target>Jon Dette</target></link><space/>– drums (1996–1997)</sentence></listitem></list><heading level="3">Timeline</heading><paragraph><xhtml:div xmlns:xhtml="" class="left"><paragraph><extension extension_name="timeline"><paragraph><sentence id="73575/252">ImageSize = width:800 height:400PlotArea = left:110 bottom:120 top:0 right:30Alignbars = justifyDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyyPeriod = from:01/01/1981 till:06/02/2011TimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy</sentence></paragraph><paragraph><sentence id="73575/253">Colors =</sentence></paragraph><preblock><preline>id:drums;percussion value:blue legend:Drums</preline><preline>id:bassvocals value:red legend:Bass&amp;nbsp;guitar,&amp;nbsp;Lead&amp;nbsp;Vocals</preline><preline>id:guitar value:green legend:Guitar</preline><preline>id:lines value:black legend:Studio&amp;nbsp;albums</preline></preblock><paragraph><sentence id="73575/